'''Romelu Lukaku Bolingoli''' ({{IPA|nl|ˈroːmeːlu luˈkaːku}}; born 13 May 1993) is a Belgian professional [[footballer]] who plays as a [[Striker (association football)|striker]] for {{Italian football updater|Napoli}} club [[SSC Napoli|Napoli]] and the [[Belgium national football team|Belgium national team]]. Lukaku ranks second for the [[List of men's footballers with 50 or more international goals|all-time European men's top goalscorers]] in international football, with 90 goals.

Lukaku began his senior club career playing for [[R.S.C. Anderlecht|Anderlecht]], where he won a [[2009–10 Belgian Pro League|Belgian Pro League]] title and finished as the league's [[2009–10 Belgian Pro League#Top goalscorers|top goalscorer]]. In 2011, he joined Chelsea in a [[Transfer (association football)|transfer]] worth £10&nbsp;million (€12&nbsp;million), but limited playing time resulted in [[Loan (association football)|loans]] to [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] and [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]; in 2014, Lukaku signed with Everton in a then [[List of most expensive association football transfers|club-record transfer]] worth £28&nbsp;million (€32&nbsp;million), going on to finish as the league's [[2016–17 Premier League#Top scorers|second-top goalscorer]]. He subsequently signed with [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in a transfer worth £75&nbsp;million (€85&nbsp;million), but after a breakdown in relations with the club, Lukaku departed for [[Inter Milan]] in 2019, in a club-record deal worth €80&nbsp;million (£68.1&nbsp;million), where he won a [[2020–21 Serie A|Serie A]] title and the [[Serie A Awards|Serie A Most Valuable Player]] award.

In 2021, Lukaku returned to Chelsea in a club-record transfer worth £97.5&nbsp;million (€115&nbsp;million), becoming the [[List of most expensive association football transfers#Highest transfer records in association football|seventh-most expensive player]], the most expensive Belgian player and, at the time, the most expensive player of all time in cumulative transfer fees. However, after one season, he was sent out on loan back to Italy to Inter Milan and [[AS Roma|Roma]] before joining another Italian club, Napoli, on a permanent deal, where he won a [[2024–25 Serie A|second Serie A title]].

[[List of international goals scored by Romelu Lukaku|Belgium's all-time top goalscorer]], Lukaku made his senior international debut in 2010, and has represented his country at six major tournaments: the [[UEFA Euro 2016|2016]], [[UEFA Euro 2020|2020]] and [[UEFA Euro 2024|2024]] [[UEFA European Championship]]s and the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014]], [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018]] and [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022]] [[FIFA World Cup]]s; he finished as joint second-highest goalscorer to win the [[FIFA World Cup awards#Golden Boot|Bronze Boot]] in 2018.

==Club career==
===Early career===
Lukaku joined his local team [[K. Rupel Boom F.C.|Rupel Boom]] at age five. After four seasons at Rupel Boom, Lukaku was discovered by scouts of [[Lierse S.K. (1906)|Lierse]], a [[Belgian Pro League]] club with an established youth academy. He played for Lierse from 2004 until 2006, scoring 121 goals in 68 matches.<ref name=LukakuYouth>{{cite news |url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/2896/premier-league/2011/01/17/2309143/romelu-lukaku-the-full-interview-teenage-sensation-reveals |title=The Full Interview: Teenage Sensation Reveals All About His Life, Loves And His Footballing 'Gift From God' |website=Goal.com |date=17 January 2011 |access-date=20 January 2011 |archive-date=18 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618230408/http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/2896/premier-league/2011/01/17/2309143/romelu-lukaku-the-full-interview-teenage-sensation-reveals |url-status=live }}</ref> After Lierse were relegated from the Belgian Pro League, [[R.S.C. Anderlecht|Anderlecht]] purchased 13 youth players from Lierse in the 2006 mid-season, including Lukaku. He played three more years as a youth player with Anderlecht, scoring 131 goals in 93 matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inter.it/en/squadra/G1034/romelu-lukaku|title=Romelu Lukaku|publisher=Inter Milan|access-date=30 November 2019|archive-date=27 July 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210727084658/https://www.inter.it/en/squadra/G1034/romelu-lukaku|url-status=dead}}</ref>

===Anderlecht===
[[File:Romelu Lukaku.jpg|thumb|130px|upright|left|Lukaku during his time at [[R.S.C. Anderlecht|Anderlecht]] in 2010]]

When Lukaku turned 16 on 13 May 2009, he signed a professional contract with Anderlecht lasting until 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.footgoal.net/suite.php?selection=43883 |title=Lukaku : " Je sais que je serai récompensé de mes efforts " |website=FootGoal.net |date=2 September 2009 |access-date=17 November 2010 |language=fr |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090903180212/http://www.footgoal.net/suite.php?selection=43883 |archive-date=3 September 2009 }}</ref> Eleven days later, he made his Belgian First Division debut on 24 May 2009 in the [[2008–09 Belgian First Division#Championship playoff|championship play-off]] match against [[Standard Liège]] as a 69th-minute [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] for [[Defender (association football)|defender]] [[Víctor Bernárdez]].<ref name=StandardBelgi>{{cite news|title=Standard is opnieuw kampioen van België|url=http://www.sporza.be/cm/sporza/voetbal/Jupiler_Pro_League/2.5503/MF_090524_STA_AND|publisher=Sporza|date=24 May 2009|access-date=26 May 2009|language=nl|archive-date=15 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140515182417/http://www.sporza.be/cm/sporza/voetbal/Jupiler_Pro_League/2.5503/MF_090524_STA_AND|url-status=live}}</ref> Anderlecht lost the match 1–0. Lukaku became a regular member of Anderlecht's first team during the [[2009–10 R.S.C. Anderlecht season|2009–10 season]], scoring his first goal at senior level against [[S.V. Zulte Waregem|Zulte Waregem]] in the 89th minute after coming on as substitute for [[Kanu (footballer, born 1987)|Kanu]] on 28 August 2009. "After scoring I dived into a sea of happiness", he told Berend Scholten from ''UEFA.com''. "You think you are flying and can take on the whole world".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=1457433.html|title=Lukaku fast-tracked to the top|date=2 March 2010|access-date=6 March 2010|publisher=UEFA|archive-date=8 March 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100308033601/http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=1457433.html|url-status=dead}}</ref> He ended the season as the top goalscorer in the [[2009–10 Belgian Pro League|Pro League]] with 15 goals as Anderlecht won its 30th [[List of Belgian football champions|Belgian title]].<ref name=punches>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2010/apr/01/romelu-lukaku-anderlecht|title=Anderlecht's Romelu Lukaku punches his weight and some – aged only 16|date=2 April 2010|access-date=13 April 2014|newspaper=The Guardian|archive-date=24 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624204458/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2010/apr/01/romelu-lukaku-anderlecht|url-status=live}}</ref> He also scored four goals during the club's run to the last 16 of the [[2009–10 UEFA Europa League]].<ref name=punches/> During the [[2010–11 Belgian Pro League|2010–11 season]], Lukaku scored 20 goals in all competitions, but Anderlecht failed to retain their league title despite finishing top of the table during the regular season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/2896/premier-league/2011/08/28/2640475/chelsea-striker-romelu-lukaku-dreams-of-playing-alongside|title=Chelsea striker Romelu Lukaku dreams of playing alongside his brother Jordan|date=28 August 2011|access-date=13 April 2014|website=Goal.com|archive-date=24 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624204612/http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/2896/premier-league/2011/08/28/2640475/chelsea-striker-romelu-lukaku-dreams-of-playing-alongside|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Chelsea===
[[File:Romelu Lukaku Chelsea vs AS-Roma 10AUG2013.jpg|thumb|140px|upright|right|Lukaku warming up for [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in 2013]]

====Transfer====
In August 2011, Lukaku joined [[Premier League]] club [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] on a five-year contract for a fee reported to be around €12&nbsp;million (£10&nbsp;million), rising to €20&nbsp;million (£17&nbsp;million) in add-ons.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nieuwsblad.be/sportwereld/cnt/DC3DOMDV|title=Chelsea betaalt 12 miljoen voor Lukaku (maar het kan oplopen tot 20 miljoen)|publisher=Sportwereld|date=12 August 2011|access-date=23 February 2013|archive-date=18 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120818210809/http://www.nieuwsblad.be/sportwereld/cnt/DC3DOMDV|url-status=live}}</ref>

====2011–12: Debut season====
Lukaku made his debut at Stamford Bridge in a 3–1 victory over [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] in the 83rd minute, coming on as a substitute for [[Fernando Torres]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/14600575 |title=Chelsea 3–1 Norwich |website=BBC Sport |date=27 August 2011 |access-date=29 December 2011 |archive-date=20 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120120043206/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/14600575.stm |url-status=live }}</ref> Lukaku made his first start for Chelsea in the [[2011–12 Football League Cup|League Cup]] against [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]]. Chelsea went on to win the match on [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalties]]. He spent the majority of the season playing for the [[Chelsea F.C. Reserves and Academy|reserves]] and started his first Premier League match on 13 May 2012, against [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]], and turned in a [[man of the match]] performance, providing an [[Assist (association football)|assist]] for [[John Terry]]'s opener.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/chelsea-cruise-against-blackburn-rovers-ahead-of-champions-league-final-in-munich-7743453.html |location=London |newspaper=The Independent |first=Nick |last=Szczepanik |date=14 May 2012 |title=Chelsea cruise against Blackburn Rovers ahead of Champions League final in Munich |access-date=3 November 2017 |archive-date=17 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120517040024/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/chelsea-cruise-against-blackburn-rovers-ahead-of-champions-league-final-in-munich-7743453.html |url-status=live }}</ref> However, Lukaku stressed he was disappointed with his involvement at the end of his debut season, revealing that, after his side's [[UEFA Champions League]] win in [[2012 UEFA Champions League Final|the final]] on 19 May, he refused to hold the trophy, explaining "it wasn't me, but my team that won".<ref>{{cite news|title=Romelu Lukaku felt no joy at Chelsea's Champions League win|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/18284627|website=BBC Sport|date=31 May 2012|access-date=24 August 2012|archive-date=4 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120804161249/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18284627|url-status=live}}</ref>

====2012–13: Loan to West Bromwich Albion====
[[File:Romelu Lukaku kick off Fulham v WBA (cropped).jpg|thumb|140px|upright|left|Lukaku playing for [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] in 2012]]

After speculation linking Lukaku with a [[Loan (association football)|loan]] move to Fulham,<ref>{{cite news|title=Fulham in talks to loan Lukaku from rivals Chelsea|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/2896/premier-league/2012/07/17/3245447/fulham-in-talks-to-loan-lukaku-from-rivals-chelsea|website=Goal.com|date=17 July 2012|access-date=24 August 2012|archive-date=24 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624204358/http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/2896/premier-league/2012/07/17/3245447/fulham-in-talks-to-loan-lukaku-from-rivals-chelsea|url-status=live}}</ref> on 10 August 2012, he joined [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] on a season-long loan deal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chelseafc.com/page/LatestNews/0,,10268~2877749,00.html |title=LUKAKU WEST BROM LOAN |publisher=Chelsea F.C. |date=10 August 2012 |access-date=10 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120811235319/http://www.chelseafc.com/page/LatestNews/0,,10268~2877749,00.html |archive-date=11 August 2012 }}</ref> He scored his first league goal eight days later, coming on as a substitute in the 77th minute in a 3–0 win against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/19221306 |title=West Brom 3–0 Liverpool |website=BBC Sport |date=18 August 2012 |access-date=3 September 2013 |first=Phil |last=McNulty |archive-date=10 October 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141010151038/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19221306 |url-status=live }}</ref> He made his full debut in a win against [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] at [[The Hawthorns]], scoring the match's only goal.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/19614964 |title=West Brom 1–0 Reading |website=BBC Sport |date=22 September 2012 |access-date=14 January 2013 |archive-date=14 November 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121114082443/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19614964 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 24 November, Lukaku came on as a 70th-minute substitute for [[Shane Long]] and netted a penalty and provided an assist to [[Marc-Antoine Fortuné]], as West Brom defeated [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] 4–2 away at the [[Stadium of Light]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/20374862|title=Sunderland 2–4 West Brom|work=BBC Sport|access-date=18 August 2020|archive-date=27 October 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201027161347/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/20374862|url-status=live}}</ref> The win proved to be West Brom's fourth consecutive win in the top flight for the first time since 1980.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/20374862 |title=West Brom went third in the Premier League after recording four successive top-flight wins for the first time since 1980 with victory at Sunderland. |website=BBC Sport |date=24 November 2012 |access-date=5 February 2013 |archive-date=28 November 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121128194636/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20374862 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 12 January 2013, Lukaku had his first multi-goal game in the Premier League, giving West Brom a 2–0 lead against Reading, before a late comeback gave the Berkshire club a 3–2 victory at the [[Madejski Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=345848&cc=5901 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130411005527/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=345848&cc=5901 |url-status=dead |archive-date=11 April 2013 |title=Reading 3–2 West Bromwich Albion |website=ESPN Soccernet |date=12 January 2013 }}</ref> In the face of claims he wanted to stay with West Brom for another year, Lukaku confirmed to the press he still wished to become a legend at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11661/8474316/Romelu-Lukaku-believes-he-can-become-a-legend-at-Chelsea |title=Romelu Lukaku believes he can become a legend at Chelsea |website=Sky Sports |date=5 February 2013 |access-date=5 February 2013 |archive-date=25 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221225092415/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11661/8474316/Romelu-Lukaku-believes-he-can-become-a-legend-at-Chelsea |url-status=live }}</ref> On 11 February, Lukaku came on as a substitute and scored his tenth Premier League goal of the season against Liverpool in a match that ended 2–0.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/21318809 |title=Gareth McAuley and Romelu Lukaku scored late goals as West Brom pinched a remarkable victory at Liverpool to end a sequence of six games without a win. |website=BBC Sport |date=11 February 2013 |access-date=12 February 2018 |archive-date=28 December 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131228113459/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21318809 |url-status=live }}</ref>

He scored his second brace of the campaign, scoring both goals for West Brom in their 2–1 home defeat of Sunderland on 23 February.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/21482987|title=West Brom 2–1 Sunderland|work=BBC Sport|access-date=18 August 2020|archive-date=23 August 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210823053032/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/21482987|url-status=live}}</ref> On 9 March, in a league match against [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]], Lukaku scored the equalising goal before having a penalty kick saved; West Brom eventually won the game courtesy of a [[Jonathan de Guzmán]] own goal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/21639482 |title=Romelu Lukaku continued his good form as West Brom beat Swansea to move up to seventh in the Premier League. |website=BBC Sport |date=9 March 2013 |access-date=12 February 2018 |archive-date=28 December 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131228145901/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21639482 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 19 May, coming on as a second-half substitute, Lukaku scored a remarkable second-half [[perfect hat-trick]], as West Brom came from three goals down to draw 5–5 in the season's final home match against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/w-brom-vs-man-utd/report/261938|title=Sir Alex Ferguson signs off with thriller as Manchester United draw 5–5 with West Brom|website=Sky Sports|access-date=23 October 2020|archive-date=24 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141224171048/http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/261938/report|url-status=live}}</ref> The match was [[Alex Ferguson]]'s 1,500th and last match in charge of United, and the highest-scoring draw in the history of the [[Premier League records and statistics|Premier League]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/may/19/west-bromwich-albion-manchester-united-premier-league-match-report |title=Manchester United share 10 goals with West Brom in Alex Ferguson's finale |newspaper=The Guardian |date=19 May 2013 |access-date=19 May 2013 |archive-date=15 August 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220815114141/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/may/19/west-bromwich-albion-manchester-united-premier-league-match-report |url-status=live }}</ref> Despite being loaned out by the club, Lukaku outscored all of his Chelsea teammates in the Premier League that season, being the sixth-highest goalscorer of the [[2012–13 Premier League|2012–13 season]] with 17 goals.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://metro.co.uk/2014/01/18/will-romelu-lukaku-come-back-to-haunt-west-bromwich-albion-4267677/|title=Will Romelu Lukaku come back to haunt West Bromwich Albion?|date=18 January 2014|access-date=4 August 2014|newspaper=Metro|archive-date=11 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140811030617/http://metro.co.uk/2014/01/18/will-romelu-lukaku-come-back-to-haunt-west-bromwich-albion-4267677/|url-status=live}}</ref> Lukaku played two Premier League matches for Chelsea at the beginning of the [[2013–14 Chelsea F.C. season|2013–14 season]]. He also came on as a substitute in the [[2013 UEFA Super Cup]], ultimately missing the deciding penalty in the shootout, as [[Manuel Neuer]] saved his shot and Chelsea lost to [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]].<ref name="super13">{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefasupercup/history/season=2013/|title=UEFA Super Cup – 2013: Neuer puts an end to Chelsea hopes|publisher=UEFA|access-date=30 September 2018|archive-date=16 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616144608/http://www.uefa.com/uefasupercup/history/season=2013/|url-status=dead}}</ref>

====2013–14: Loan to Everton====
[[File:Romelu Lukaku 2014-05-03.jpg|thumb|upright|Lukaku pre-match with [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] in 2014]]

On the final day of the summer 2013 transfer window, Lukaku joined [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] on a season-long loan.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11671/8903847/transfer-deadline-day-everton-sign-james-mccarthy-and-romelu-lukaku |title=Transfer deadline day: Everton sign James McCarthy and Romelu Lukaku, Lukaku scored on his debut after replacing Steven Naismith at half time. |website=Sky Sports |date=3 September 2013 |access-date=3 September 2013 |archive-date=5 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220605130020/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11671/8903847/transfer-deadline-day-everton-sign-james-mccarthy-and-romelu-lukaku |url-status=live }}</ref> The striker made his début for the Toffees away to [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] on 21 September 2013, scoring the winning goal in a 3–2 victory for Everton. During the header, he had a collision with a West Ham defender and was taken off the pitch for some treatment. The physio had to tell him he had scored the winner.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/24089772|title=West Ham 2–3 Everton|date=21 September 2013|website=BBC Sport|access-date=12 February 2018|archive-date=4 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171104095513/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/24089772|url-status=live}}</ref> He scored twice on his home debut nine days later in a 3–2 win against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]], as well assisting [[Ross Barkley]]'s goal.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/24201002 |title=Everton 3–2 Newcastle |website=BBC Sport |date=30 September 2013 |access-date=7 October 2013 |archive-date=6 October 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131006002349/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24201002 |url-status=live }}</ref> He then opened the scoring in a 3–1 defeat to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in the following match.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/24350210 |title=Manchester City 3–1 Everton |website=BBC Sport |date=5 October 2013 |access-date=7 October 2013 |archive-date=6 October 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131006074859/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24350210 |url-status=live }}</ref> He continued his impressive start at the club by netting the opening goal in a 2–0 win over [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]], and then scored twice in the first [[Merseyside derby]] of the season, as Everton drew 3–3 against Liverpool, with Lukaku stating afterwards it was the best experience he had had in his short career.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/24591399 |title=Aston Villa 0–2 Everton |work=BBC Sport |access-date=1 December 2013 |archive-date=10 December 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131210145406/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24591399 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11671/9043000/romelu-lukaku-claims-evertons-draw-with-liverpool-is-the-best-derby-he-has-played-in |title=Romelu Lukaku claims Everton's draw with Liverpool is the 'best derby' he has played in |website=Sky Sports |access-date=1 December 2013 |archive-date=3 December 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203014636/http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11671/9043000/romelu-lukaku-claims-evertons-draw-with-liverpool-is-the-best-derby-he-has-played-in |url-status=live }}</ref>

In January 2014, Lukaku was named by ''[[The Guardian]]'' as one of the ten most promising young players in Europe,<ref name="top10list">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2014/jan/19/next-10-big-things-europes-top-youngsters|title=The next 10 big things: Europe's top youngsters and stars of the future|date=18 January 2014|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=13 December 2016|archive-date=12 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612144504/https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2014/jan/19/next-10-big-things-europes-top-youngsters|url-status=live}}</ref> but later in the month was taken off on a stretcher with an ankle ligament injury after [[Gareth Barry]] slipped and slid into the striker, as he attempted to block [[Steven Gerrard]]'s opening goal in the Merseyside derby against Liverpool.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/25822244 |title=Romelu Lukaku: Everton striker out for 'weeks rather than months' |work=BBC Sport |access-date=29 January 2013 |archive-date=28 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140128022301/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/25822244 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/25822244 |title=Liverpool 4–0 Everton |work=BBC Sport |access-date=29 January 2014 |archive-date=29 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140129025306/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/25822244 |url-status=live }}</ref> Lukaku made his return from injury against West Ham in March 2014, scoring the only goal of the match on the 81st minute after coming on as a second-half substitute.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/26300994 |title=Everton 1–0 West Ham |work=BBC Sport |access-date=1 March 2014 |archive-date=1 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301173129/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/26300994 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 6 April, he scored one goal and assisted another as Everton beat [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] 3–0 at [[Goodison Park]] to record a sixth consecutive Premier League win.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/26807037|title=Everton 3–0 Arsenal|date=6 April 2014|access-date=13 April 2014|website=BBC Sport|archive-date=12 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140412215213/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/26807037|url-status=live}}</ref> His final goal for the loan period came on the last day of the season as he scored the second in a 2–0 win over [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/27273312 |title=Hull City 0–2 Everton |work=BBC Sport |access-date=26 May 2014 |archive-date=12 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512042518/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27273312 |url-status=live }}</ref> Lukaku found the net 15 times in 31 league matches to help Everton to fifth place, with a club record of 72 Premier League points.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.evertonfc.com/news/archive/2014/05/14/magic-numbers-roberto-s-record-breakers |title=Magic Numbers: Roberto's Record-Breakers |publisher=Everton FC |access-date=26 May 2014 |archive-date=15 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140515151612/http://www.evertonfc.com/news/archive/2014/05/14/magic-numbers-roberto-s-record-breakers |url-status=dead }}</ref>

===Everton===
====2014–16: Rise to stardom====
[[File:Romelu Lukaku vs Dinamo Kyiv (16869431132) (cropped).jpg|thumb|180px|left|Lukaku playing for Everton in 2015]]

Lukaku signed a five-year contract with Everton in July 2014 for a then-club record fee of £28&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/28569197|website=BBC Sport|access-date=27 June 2017|date=30 July 2014|title=Romelu Lukaku: Everton sign Chelsea striker|archive-date=29 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180629154653/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/28569197|url-status=live}}</ref> He scored his first goal as a permanent player on 13 September, against his former club West Brom. Lukaku [[Goal celebration#Notable non-celebrations|did not celebrate the goal]], and was applauded by the West Brom fans for his sign of respect. On 19 February 2015, Lukaku scored his first hat-trick in a 4–1 win for Everton against [[BSC Young Boys|Young Boys]] in the [[UEFA Europa League]] last 32; he struck with a header, a right-foot shot and a left-foot shot.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/31523676|title=BSC Young Boys 1–4 Everton|date=30 July 2014|access-date=30 July 2014|website=BBC Sport|archive-date=21 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150221063813/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31523676|url-status=live}}</ref> He added another two goals in a 3–1 win in the second leg a week later.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Baker|first1=Ian|title=Everton 3–1 BSC Young Boys|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/31627528|access-date=27 February 2015|website=BBC Sport|date=26 February 2015|archive-date=26 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150226094146/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31627528|url-status=live}}</ref> With eight goals, he was the tournament's joint highest scorer that season, alongside [[Alan Carvalho|Alan]] of [[FC Red Bull Salzburg|Red Bull Salzburg]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Alan and Everton's Lukaku finish as top scorers|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/0221-0e90e477c833-c69a3e0278c0-1000--alan-and-everton-s-lukaku-finish-as-top-scorers/|access-date=27 May 2015|publisher=UEFA|date=27 May 2015|archive-date=23 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623170110/http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=2249783.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

In the second game of the [[2015–16 Premier League]] season, Lukaku scored a first-half double in Everton's 3–0 win at [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] on 15 August 2015 with his first two shots on target. Before the match, he presented a t-shirt to a home fan whom he had accidentally struck with the ball during shooting practice.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lewis|first1=Aimee|title=Southampton 0–3 Everton|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/33832170|access-date=16 August 2015|website=BBC Sport|date=15 August 2015|archive-date=16 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150816074906/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/33832170|url-status=live}}</ref> On 26 August, he scored another brace in a 5–3 extra-time win over [[EFL League One|League One]] side [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] in the [[2015–16 Football League Cup|League Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Barnsley 3–5 Everton (AET) |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/33969808 |date=26 August 2015 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=27 August 2015 |archive-date=28 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150828070838/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/33969808 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 28 September, Lukaku scored twice and assisted the other against West Brom as he managed to guide his team from losing 2–0 to winning 2–3.<ref>{{cite news|title=West Brom 2–3 Everton|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34311167|access-date=4 October 2015|website=BBC Sport|date=28 September 2015|archive-date=1 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151001113931/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34311167|url-status=live}}</ref> He scored against Liverpool the following week in a 1–1 draw at Goodison Park.<ref>{{cite news|title=Everton 2–3 Liverpool|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34372497|access-date=4 October 2015|website=BBC Sport|date=4 October 2015|archive-date=4 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151004094617/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34372497|url-status=live}}</ref> On 21 November, Lukaku scored twice in a 4–0 win over Aston Villa, becoming the fifth player under 23 years of age to score at least fifty Premier League goals, after [[Robbie Fowler]], [[Michael Owen]], [[Wayne Rooney]] and [[Cristiano Ronaldo]].<ref name="becomes">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/romelu-lukaku-only-5th-player-6878148|title=After Lukaku, can YOU name the four Prem players to score 50 before age of 23?|first=Aaron|last=Flanagan|date=22 November 2015|newspaper=Daily Mirror|access-date=23 October 2020|archive-date=30 October 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201030160514/https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/romelu-lukaku-only-5th-player-6878148|url-status=live}}</ref> On 7 December, Lukaku scored a close-range goal in a 1–1 draw against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]], his 50th in 100 appearances in all competitions for Everton.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/everton-vs-c-palace/report/341329|title=Everton 1–1 Crystal Palace: Romelu Lukaku secures point for hosts|website=Sky Sports|access-date=11 May 2021|archive-date=27 October 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201027141903/https://www.skysports.com/football/everton-vs-c-palace/report/341329|url-status=live}}</ref> On 12 December, Lukaku became the first Everton player to score in six consecutive Premier League matches, and the first to score in seven consecutive matches in all competitions since [[Bob Latchford]] forty years previously, when he opened the scoring in the Toffees' 1–1 draw with Norwich City at [[Carrow Road]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/sport/can-romelu-lukaku-break-jamie-vardys-premier-league-goalscoring-record-711126.html|title=Can Romelu Lukaku break Jamie Vardy's Premier League goalscoring record?|date=12 December 2015|newspaper=Irish Examiner|access-date=13 December 2015|archive-date=15 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151215052112/http://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/sport/can-romelu-lukaku-break-jamie-vardys-premier-league-goalscoring-record-711126.html|url-status=live}}</ref> In his next match, a 3–2 defeat to [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]], Lukaku became the first Everton player since [[Dave Hickson]] in 1954 to score in eight consecutive matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2015/12/19/gc-evertons-romelu-lukaku-breaks-a-61-year-record-after-goal-aga/|title=Everton's Romelu Lukaku breaks a 61-year record after goal against Leicester|first=Graham|last=Corking|work=HITC |date=19 December 2015|access-date=20 December 2015|archive-date=24 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624204311/http://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2015/12/19/gc-evertons-romelu-lukaku-breaks-a-61-year-record-after-goal-aga/|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 6 February 2016, Lukaku scored his 20th goal of the season in a 3–0 victory at [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]], meaning he was the first Everton player since [[Graeme Sharp]] to score at least twenty goals in all competitions in consecutive seasons for Everton. The strike was also his 16th league goal of the season, equalling Premier League goal scoring records for Everton set by [[Tony Cottee]] and [[Andrei Kanchelskis]] in the mid-1990s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nsno.co.uk/everton-news/2016/02/record-breaking-lukaku-happy-to-help-team/|title=Record-breaking Lukaku happy to help team - NSNO|first=Tom|last=Power|access-date=11 May 2021|archive-date=10 March 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210310014656/https://www.nsno.co.uk/everton-news/2016/02/record-breaking-lukaku-happy-to-help-team/|url-status=live}}</ref> Lukaku followed this goal with another strike in a 2–0 victory at [[AFC Bournemouth|Bournemouth]]'s [[Dean Court]] for his 21st goal of the season. This victory sent Everton into the quarter-finals of the [[2015–16 FA Cup|FA Cup]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35566556|title=Bournemouth 0–2 Everton|date=20 February 2016|website=BBC Sport|access-date=12 February 2018|archive-date=5 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180805003523/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35566556|url-status=live}}</ref> and equalled the number of goals scored in all competitions by [[Yakubu (footballer)|Yakubu]] for Everton in the [[2007–08 Everton F.C. season|2007–08 season]], the previous best in the Premier League era.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.evertonfc.com/players/y/ya/yakubu-ayegbeni|title=Yakubu Ayegbeni – Everton Football Club|access-date=1 March 2016|archive-date=8 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180708162158/http://www.evertonfc.com/players/y/ya/yakubu-ayegbeni|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 1 March, Lukaku scored in a 3–1 victory against Aston Villa at [[Villa Park]], his 17th league goal of the season, a Premier League-era record for Everton.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/match-reports/aston-villa-1-3-everton-10955746|title=Aston Villa 1–3 Everton full-time report: Blues go into top half after cruise|first=Phil|last=Kirkbride|date=1 March 2016|access-date=1 March 2016|archive-date=4 June 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220604180623/https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/match-reports/aston-villa-1-3-everton-10955746|url-status=live}}</ref> The goal also meant Lukaku had equalled his previous best goal return in a league season, set during his loan spell at West Brom in the 2012–13 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=56521|title=Romelu Lukaku &#124; Football Stats &#124; Inter Milan &#124; Age 27 &#124; Soccer Base|website=Soccerbase|access-date=11 May 2021|archive-date=10 June 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210610234923/https://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=56521|url-status=live}}</ref>

====2016–17: Sustained individual success====
[[File:Manchester United v Everton, April 2017 (06).JPG|thumb|right|Lukaku with Everton in 2017]]

On 12 September 2016, Lukaku scored his first goals of the [[2016–17 Everton F.C. season|2016–17 season]] with all three goals in a 3–0 against Sunderland at the Stadium of Light. His goals were scored in 11 minutes and 37 seconds, making it the 12th-fastest hat-trick in Premier League history.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/37273038 |title=Sunderland 0–3 Everton |date=10 September 2016 |website=[[BBC Sport]] |access-date=12 February 2018 |archive-date=17 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617001304/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/37273038 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 4 February 2017, Lukaku scored four goals, the first of which was Everton's fastest ever Premier League goal, against Bournemouth in a 6–3 victory at Goodison Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/02/04/everton-6-bournemouth-3romelu-lukaku-scores-toffees-fastest/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/02/04/everton-6-bournemouth-3romelu-lukaku-scores-toffees-fastest/ |archive-date=10 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|title=Everton 6 Bournemouth 3: Romelu Lukaku scores Toffees' fastest Premier League goal in Goodison rout |date=4 February 2017 |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]}}{{cbignore}}</ref> It was also the 300th hat-trick scored in the Premier League.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/02/07/revealed-20-premier-league-teams-have-scored-hat-tricks-history/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/02/07/revealed-20-premier-league-teams-have-scored-hat-tricks-history/ |archive-date=10 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|title=Revealed: The 20 Premier League teams who have scored most hat-tricks in history of competition|date=7 February 2017 |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|access-date=22 March 2018}}{{cbignore}}</ref> On 25 February 2017, he equalled [[Duncan Ferguson]]'s [[List of Everton F.C. records and statistics|club record]] for Premier League goals, scoring his 60th EPL goal for the Toffees in a 2–0 victory over Sunderland at Goodison Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/everton-vs-sland/356587|title=Everton 2–0 Sunderland: Romelu Lukaku equals club record in win|date=25 February 2017|website=[[Sky Sports]]|access-date=25 February 2017|archive-date=24 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624210010/http://www.skysports.com/football/everton-vs-sland/356587|url-status=live}}</ref> On 5 March, he surpassed Ferguson to become the outright record holder, scoring in a 3–2 loss against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] away at [[White Hart Lane]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/romelu-lukaku-evertons-can-you-12706546|title=ROMELU LUKAKU: EVERTON'S LEADING PREMIER LEAGUE GOALSCORER|date=7 March 2017|newspaper=[[Liverpool Echo]]|access-date=9 March 2017|archive-date=9 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170309080251/http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/romelu-lukaku-evertons-can-you-12706546|url-status=live}}</ref> In the next match, a 3–0 home win against West Brom, Lukaku scored to become the first Everton player since Bob Latchford to score 20 or more goals in all competitions for three consecutive seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/EFC_Statto/status/840604310773858304|title=EFC Statto on Twitter|access-date=11 March 2017|archive-date=2 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170402090127/https://twitter.com/efc_statto/status/840604310773858304|url-status=live}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=November 2020}} A week later, during a 4–0 victory over Hull City, he scored twice to take his league goals tally to 21 for the season, thereby becoming the first Everton player since [[Gary Lineker]] 31 years previously to surpass 20 league goals in a season, as well as being the fourth player and first foreign player to score 80 Premier League goals before the age of 24.<ref name=eighty>{{cite news|last1=Hafeez|first1=Shamoon|title=Premier League statistics: Arsenal, Mahrez, Vardy, Lukaku, Deeney|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/39318111|access-date=21 March 2017|website=[[BBC Sport]]|date=19 March 2017|archive-date=26 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180626152401/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/39318111|url-status=live}}</ref>

In March 2017, Lukaku turned down a new five-year contract worth a reported £140,000 a week amidst rumours of a return to Chelsea.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McNulty|first1=Phil|author-link1=Phil McNulty|title=Romelu Lukaku: Everton striker rejects new contract at Goodison Park|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/39273691|access-date=21 March 2017|website=[[BBC Sport]]|date=14 March 2017|archive-date=19 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719222425/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/39273691|url-status=live}}</ref> In an interview, he questioned the club's ambition to make big transfers and chase Champions League qualification, offending his manager [[Ronald Koeman]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Romelu Lukaku must respect Everton contract – Ronald Koeman|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/39295524|access-date=21 March 2017|website=[[BBC Sport]]|date=16 March 2017|archive-date=8 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180708191226/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/39295524|url-status=live}}</ref> A goal in a 3–1 win for Everton against [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] on 15 April meant Lukaku was the first Everton player since Bob Latchford to score 25 goals in two consecutive seasons in all competitions, and the first player since the legendary [[Dixie Dean]] to score in nine consecutive matches at Goodison Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/romelu-lukaku-stunning-stats-everton-12899448|title=How Lukaku has made history in stunning Everton season|first=Paul|last=Gorst|date=15 April 2017|work=[[Liverpool Echo]]|access-date=15 April 2017|archive-date=16 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170416045612/http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/romelu-lukaku-stunning-stats-everton-12899448|url-status=live}}</ref> On 20 April 2017, Lukaku was named in the [[PFA Team of the Year]] for the first time.<ref name=PFA1617>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39648483 |title=PFA teams of the year: Chelsea and Tottenham dominate Premier League XI |website=[[BBC Sport]] |date=20 April 2017 |access-date=6 May 2018 |archive-date=12 January 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210112073506/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39648483 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was also included in the six player shortlists for the [[PFA Players' Player of the Year]] and [[PFA Young Player of the Year]] awards.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thepfa.com/news/2017/4/13/pfa-mens-players-player-of-the-year|title=Men's PFA Players' Player of the Year 2017|date=13 April 2017|publisher=[[Professional Footballers' Association]]|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-date=8 June 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210608114031/https://www.thepfa.com/news/2017/4/13/pfa-mens-players-player-of-the-year|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thepfa.com/news/2017/4/13/pfa-mens-young-player-of-the-year|title=Men's PFA Young Player of the Year 2017|date=13 April 2017|publisher=[[Professional Footballers' Association]]|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170423154800/https://www.thepfa.com/news/2017/4/13/pfa-mens-young-player-of-the-year|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Manchester United===
====Transfer====
Lukaku joined Manchester United on 10 July 2017, signing a five-year contract, with the option of a further year.<ref>{{cite news |title=United sign Romelu Lukaku |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Football-News/2017/Jul/club-statement-manchester-united-confirm-romelu-lukaku-has-joined-the-club-from-everton.aspx |publisher=Manchester United F.C. |date=10 July 2017 |access-date=10 July 2017 |archive-date=6 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180506165020/http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Football-News/2017/Jul/club-statement-manchester-united-confirm-romelu-lukaku-has-joined-the-club-from-everton.aspx |url-status=live }}</ref> Although the fee was officially undisclosed, it was reported to be worth an initial £75&nbsp;million, plus £15&nbsp;million in add-ons.<ref>{{cite news |title=Romelu Lukaku: Man Utd sign Everton striker for initial £75m |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40550934 |website=BBC Sport |date=10 July 2017 |access-date=10 July 2017 |archive-date=10 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170710161610/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40550934 |url-status=live }}</ref> Thus, he became a teammate with his French-speaking close friend [[Paul Pogba]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sportsjoe.ie/football/paul-pogba-romelu-lukaku-129506 |title=Romelu Lukaku telling Paul Pogba he's joining him at Old Trafford is just beautiful |website=Sports Joe |year=2017 |access-date=23 October 2020 |archive-date=26 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201026221553/https://www.sportsjoe.ie/football/paul-pogba-romelu-lukaku-129506 |url-status=live }}</ref> Lukaku's signing came a day after former Manchester United captain Wayne Rooney left the club to return to Everton, Rooney's boyhood club.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rooney to join Everton |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Football-News/2017/Jul/wayne-rooney-is-to-rejoin-everton-from-manchester-united.aspx |publisher=Manchester United F.C. |date=10 July 2017 |access-date=10 July 2017 |archive-date=9 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170709193019/http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Football-News/2017/Jul/wayne-rooney-is-to-rejoin-everton-from-manchester-united.aspx |url-status=live }}</ref>

====2017–18: Debut season and drop in form====
[[File:Romelu Lukaku 27 September 2017 cropped.jpg|thumb|upright|Lukaku playing for [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in 2017]]

Lukaku made his debut against [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] on 8 August in the [[2017 UEFA Super Cup]], and scored his first competitive goal for the club in the 2–1 defeat.<ref name="2017USC">{{cite news |title=Real beat Man Utd in Super Cup |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40788621 |website=BBC Sport |date=8 August 2017 |access-date=13 August 2017 |archive-date=10 March 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210310235418/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/40788621 |url-status=live }}</ref> His league debut came five days later at home to West Ham. Lukaku scored twice in a 4–0 win,<ref>{{cite news |title=Manchester United 4–0 West Ham United |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40841358 |website=BBC Sport |date=13 August 2017 |access-date=13 August 2017 |archive-date=18 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618052517/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40841358 |url-status=live }}</ref> becoming the fourth Manchester United player to score two goals on his Premier League debut for the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/452144|title=Lukaku joins exclusive club with debut double|publisher=Premier League|date=14 August 2017|access-date=15 August 2017|archive-date=7 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180707010416/https://www.premierleague.com/news/452144|url-status=live}}</ref> On 12 September, he scored his first UEFA Champions League goal in a 3–0 win over [[FC Basel|Basel]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/41154816 |title=Manchester United 3–0 FC Basel |website=BBC Sport |date=12 September 2020 |access-date=23 October 2020 |archive-date=28 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201028045902/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/41154816 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 17 September, Lukaku scored United's third goal in a 4–0 win over his former club Everton, with Lukaku running over towards Everton fans and cupping his ears during his [[goal celebration]] in response to being booed throughout the game.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/everton-fans-unhappy-romelu-lukakus-13634711 |title=Everton fans unhappy with Romelu Lukaku's goal celebration |last=Prentice |first=David |date=18 September 2017 |access-date=13 October 2018 |newspaper=Liverpool Echo |archive-date=11 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190811115719/https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/everton-fans-unhappy-romelu-lukakus-13634711 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 27 September, Lukaku scored twice in a 4–1 win over [[PFC CSKA Moscow|CSKA Moscow]], taking his tally to ten goals in his first nine appearances. In doing so, he broke the record set by [[Bobby Charlton]], who had scored nine goals in his first nine appearances for the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11667/11056777/jose-mourinho-says-romelu-lukakus-form-amazing-but-man-utd-team-mates-deserve-credit-too|title=Jose Mourinho says Romelu Lukaku's form amazing but Man Utd team-mates deserve credit too|website=Sky Sports|date=28 September 2017|access-date=29 September 2017|archive-date=24 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624204518/http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11667/11056777/jose-mourinho-says-romelu-lukakus-form-amazing-but-man-utd-team-mates-deserve-credit-too|url-status=live}}</ref> In a 2–1 win over his former club Chelsea on 25 February 2018, Lukaku scored the equaliser and then assisted [[Jesse Lingard]]'s game-winning goal.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Oscroft|first1=Tim|title=Manchester United 2–1 Chelsea|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43101688|website=BBC Sport|access-date=16 March 2018|date=25 February 2018|archive-date=16 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316132115/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43101688|url-status=live}}</ref> He scored his 200th goal for club and country on 13 March in a 2–1 away defeat to [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] that eliminated Manchester United from the Champions League in the round of 16.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rodger|first1=James|title=Romelu Lukaku reacts to scoring his 200th goal as Manchester United exit Champions League|url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/romelu-lukaku-reacts-scoring-200th-14408325|newspaper=Birmingham Mail|access-date=16 March 2018|date=14 March 2018|archive-date=24 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624232751/https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/romelu-lukaku-reacts-scoring-200th-14408325|url-status=live}}</ref> On 31 March 2018, Lukaku scored to open a 2–0 home win over Swansea. It was his [[List of footballers with 100 or more Premier League goals|100th Premier League goal]] in his 216th game, and made him the fifth youngest of the 28 players to reach the tally.<ref name=sky100>{{cite news|last1=Wright|first1=Nick|title=Romelu Lukaku's 100 Premier League goals in stats|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11667/11311506/romelu-lukakus-100-premier-league-goals-in-stats|access-date=31 March 2018|website=Sky Sports|date=31 March 2018|archive-date=6 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180706191105/http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11667/11311506/romelu-lukakus-100-premier-league-goals-in-stats|url-status=live}}</ref>

====2018–19: Final season in Manchester====
Lukaku started the [[2018–19 Manchester United F.C. season|2018–19 season]] with four goals in his first five appearances, including a brace against Burnley, before a 12-game drought lasting from 19 September to 27 November 2018. Goals against Southampton and Fulham followed before the sacking of manager [[José Mourinho]], only for Mourinho's replacement – former United striker [[Ole Gunnar Solskjær]] – to leave Lukaku out of the squad entirely for his first two games in charge against [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] and [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]]. Lukaku made substitute appearances in United's next two games against Bournemouth<ref>{{cite news |first=Saj |last=Chowdhury |title=Man Utd 4–1 Bournemouth: Ole Gunnar Solskjaer says he is not purely focused on attack |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46663363 |website=BBC Sport |date=30 December 2018 |access-date=12 March 2019 |archive-date=4 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190104162439/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46663363 |url-status=live }}</ref> and Newcastle United,<ref>{{cite news |first=Neil |last=Johnston |title=Newcastle United 0–2 Manchester United: Ole Gunnar Solskjaer wins fourth game from four |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46682775 |website=BBC Sport |date=2 January 2019 |access-date=12 March 2019 |archive-date=5 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190105221653/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46682775 |url-status=live }}</ref> scoring in both matches within two minutes of coming on. He then played the full 90 minutes of the FA Cup third round tie against Reading, scoring the second goal in a 2–0 win.<ref>{{cite news |first=Matt |last=Davis |title=Manchester United 2–0 Reading in FA Cup third round |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46706809 |website=BBC Sport |date=5 January 2019 |access-date=12 March 2019 |archive-date=10 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190110160801/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46706809 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, Solskjær continued to prefer to start [[Marcus Rashford]] up front, and Lukaku started just five of the next nine games, playing the full 90 minutes in just two and failing to score in any of them. His goalscoring form returned for the next three games, as he scored braces against each of Crystal Palace,<ref>{{cite news |first=Shamoon |last=Hafez |title=Crystal Palace 1–3 Manchester United: Romelu Lukaku double helps visitors to victory |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47301088 |website=BBC Sport |date=27 February 2019 |access-date=12 March 2019 |archive-date=28 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190228000613/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47301088 |url-status=live }}</ref> Southampton<ref>{{cite news |first=Neil |last=Johnston |title=Manchester United 3–2 Southampton |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47340490 |website=BBC Sport |date=2 March 2019 |access-date=12 March 2019 |archive-date=2 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302171633/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47340490 |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]]. The goals against PSG were part of a 3–1 win that saw United through to the [[2018–19 UEFA Champions League knockout phase|Champions League quarter-finals]] on the away goals rule, the first time any team had progressed after losing at home in the first leg by two goals or more.<ref>{{cite news |first=Shamoon |last=Hafez |title=Champions League: PSG 1–3 Man Utd (agg: 3–3) |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47461886 |website=BBC Sport |date=6 March 2019 |access-date=12 March 2019 |archive-date=30 August 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210830003654/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47461886 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, United were eliminated by [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] in the quarter-finals 4–0 on aggregate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://soccer.nbcsports.com/2019/04/16/messi-barcelona-knock-manchester-united-out-of-champions-league-video/|title=Messi, Barcelona knock Manchester United out of Champions League (video)|first=Nicholas|last=Mendola|date=16 April 2019|access-date=21 August 2020|archive-date=19 September 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200919125418/https://soccer.nbcsports.com/2019/04/16/messi-barcelona-knock-manchester-united-out-of-champions-league-video/|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Inter Milan===
====2019–20: Club record transfer and Europa League runner-up====
Lukaku joined Italian club [[Inter Milan]] on 8 August 2019, signing a five-year contract for a fee reported to be a club record €80&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inter.it/en/news/68541/romelu-lukaku-signs-for-inter|title=Romelu Lukaku signs for Inter|publisher=Inter Milan|access-date=8 August 2019|archive-date=8 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808150242/https://www.inter.it/en/news/68541/romelu-lukaku-signs-for-inter|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Lukaku: Inter Milan sign Belgium striker from Manchester United for £74m|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/49146040|website=BBC Sport|date=8 August 2019|access-date=8 August 2019|archive-date=8 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190808151827/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49146040|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Romelu Lukaku: Inter Milan agree £73m fee for Manchester United striker |url=https://www.skysports.com/transfer/news/11667/11779538/romelu-lukaku-inter-milan-agree-73m-fee-for-manchester-united-striker |website=Sky Sports |date=8 August 2019 |access-date=10 August 2019 |archive-date=27 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190827044626/https://www.skysports.com/transfer/news/11667/11779538/romelu-lukaku-inter-milan-agree-73m-fee-for-manchester-united-striker |url-status=live }}</ref> He later mentioned the reasons for leaving Manchester United, by claiming that he was made a scapegoat alongside other players, such as Paul Pogba and [[Alexis Sánchez]], in addition to club's failure to protect him against rumours about his future.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://talksport.com/football/590950/romelu-lukaku-scapegoat-manchester-united-paul-pogba-alexis-sanchez/ |title=WASN'T ME Romelu Lukaku claims he was made a scapegoat at Manchester United alongside Paul Pogba and Alexis Sanchez |website=Talksport |date=22 August 2019 |access-date=23 October 2020 |archive-date=26 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201026105857/https://talksport.com/football/590950/romelu-lukaku-scapegoat-manchester-united-paul-pogba-alexis-sanchez/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Lukaku made his debut for Inter on 26 August in the opening [[Serie A]] matchday against [[U.S. Lecce|Lecce]], netting his side's third goal with his first shot in a 4–0 home win.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.sports.yahoo.com/news/lukaku-scores-debut-contes-inter-220352594.html|title=Lukaku scores on debut as Conte's Inter make a flying start|website=Yahoo Sports|date=26 August 2019|access-date=22 July 2024|archive-date=5 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210105045518/https://uk.sports.yahoo.com/news/lukaku-scores-debut-contes-inter-220352594.html|url-status=live|agency=Reuters}}</ref> The goal meant that Lukaku has found the net in his first league game for five of the six clubs he has represented: Anderlecht, West Brom, Everton, Manchester United and Inter;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/lukaku-inter-goal-man-utd-16819923|title=Former Manchester United striker Romelu Lukaku scores on Inter Milan debut|newspaper=Manchester Evening News|first=Joe|last=Bray|date=26 August 2019|access-date=28 August 2019|archive-date=28 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190828094914/https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/lukaku-inter-goal-man-utd-16819923|url-status=live}}</ref> he also become only the third Belgian to score for Inter in Serie A, after [[Enzo Scifo]] and [[Radja Nainggolan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inter.it/en/news/68659/inter-vs-lecce-all-you-need-to-know|title=Inter vs. Lecce, all you need to know|publisher=Inter Milan|date=27 August 2019|access-date=28 August 2019|archive-date=28 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190828094905/https://www.inter.it/en/news/68659/inter-vs-lecce-all-you-need-to-know|url-status=dead}}</ref> In the club's second league game of the season at [[Cagliari Calcio|Cagliari]] on 1 September, Lukaku scored the match-winning goal from the penalty spot to give Inter a 2–1 victory away from home; however, he was subject to [[Racism in association football|racial abuse]] from some of the Cagliari fans.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/49546433 |title=Cagliari 1–2 Inter |website=BBC Sport |date=1 September 2019 |access-date=1 September 2019 |archive-date=3 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190903031220/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/49546433 |url-status=live }}</ref>

In the first months since his arrival, Lukaku formed an attacking partnership with Argentine youngster [[Lautaro Martínez]], dubbed "Lu-La" by Italian media.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inter.it/en/news/2019/10/20/lautaro-martinez-post-match-sassuolo-inter.html|title=Lautaro: "The understanding with Lukaku is improving game by game"|publisher=Inter Milan|date=20 October 2019|access-date=9 August 2020|archive-date=7 July 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220707021444/https://www.inter.it/en/news/2019/10/20/lautaro-martinez-post-match-sassuolo-inter.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sempreinter.com/2019/10/22/romelu-lukaku-lautaro-martinezs-partnership-continuing-to-go-from-strength-to-strength/|title=Romelu Lukaku & Lautaro Martinez's Partnership Continuing To Go From Strength To Strength|website=Sempre Inter|date=22 October 2019|access-date=9 August 2020|archive-date=19 September 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230919220555/https://sempreinter.com/2019/10/22/romelu-lukaku-lautaro-martinezs-partnership-continuing-to-go-from-strength-to-strength/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://forzaitalianfootball.com/2019/10/tired-inter-running-on-fumes-and-lula/|title=Tired Inter running on fumes and Lula|website=Forza Italian Football|first=Adriano|last=Boin|date=30 October 2019|access-date=9 August 2020|archive-date=19 September 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230919224701/https://forzaitalianfootball.com/2019/10/tired-inter-running-on-fumes-and-lula/|url-status=live}}</ref> This came after the duo scored a brace each in the 4–3 away win against [[U.S. Sassuolo Calcio|Sassuolo]] in October, giving Inter their first triumph there since 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inter.it/en/news/2019/10/21/all-you-need-to-know-sassuolo-inter.html|title=Sassuolo 3–4 Inter, all you need to know|publisher=Inter Milan|date=21 October 2019|access-date=9 August 2020|archive-date=7 July 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220707013545/https://www.inter.it/en/news/2019/10/21/all-you-need-to-know-sassuolo-inter.html|url-status=live}}</ref> On 2 November, Lukaku scored a brace in a 2–1 away win over [[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]] in Serie A, which saw him match [[Ronaldo (Brazilian footballer)|Ronaldo]]'s record of nine goals in his first eleven league appearances for the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.football-italia.net/145990/lukaku-ronaldo|title=Lukaku like Ronaldo|website=Football Italia|date=3 November 2019|access-date=4 November 2019|archive-date=4 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104160223/https://www.football-italia.net/145990/lukaku-ronaldo|url-status=live}}</ref> On 27 November, Lukaku scored his first UEFA Champions League goal for Inter, in a 3–1 away win against [[SK Slavia Prague|Slavia Prague]] in the group stage; in addition to that, he also assisted the two other goals scored by Martínez, and had two goals disallowed himself.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inter.it/en/news/2019/11/28/match-review-slavia-prague-inter.html|title=Match review: Slavia Prague 1–3 Inter|publisher=Inter Milan|date=28 November 2019|access-date=9 August 2020|archive-date=28 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191128154911/https://www.inter.it/en/news/2019/11/28/match-review-slavia-prague-inter.html|url-status=live}}</ref> In the final match at home against Barcelona, Lukaku scored his side's only goal in a 2–1 defeat, meaning that Inter transferred to Europa League for the second season in a row.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inter.it/en/news/2019/12/10/inter-barcelona-champions-league-2019-2020.html|title=Inter 1–2 Barcelona, the Nerazzurri eliminated from the Champions League|publisher=Inter Milan|date=10 December 2019|access-date=9 August 2020|archive-date=3 May 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210503165633/https://www.inter.it/en/news/2019/12/10/inter-barcelona-champions-league-2019-2020.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

He began the new year on 6 January by scoring a brace in a 3–1 win against [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]], giving Inter their first league win at [[Stadio San Paolo]] since October 1997;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inter.it/en/news/2020/01/07/statistics-napoli-inter-1-3.html|title=Napoli 1–3 Inter, all you need to know|publisher=Inter Milan|date=7 January 2020|access-date=9 August 2020|archive-date=21 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210421230335/https://www.inter.it/en/news/2020/01/07/statistics-napoli-inter-1-3.html|url-status=live}}</ref> he earned praise from the media for his first goal scored in the 14th minute, which came from an individual effort.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/lukaku-dominates-inter-beat-napoli-215334814.html|title=Lukaku dominates as Inter beat Napoli, stay level with Juve (video)|website=Yahoo Sports|date=6 January 2020|access-date=9 August 2020|archive-date=7 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200107195627/https://sports.yahoo.com/lukaku-dominates-inter-beat-napoli-215334814.html|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 9 February, Lukaku scored the final goal of the 4–2 home win over [[Derby della Madonnina|cross-town rivals]] [[A.C. Milan|Milan]], sending Inter to the top of the table and giving them another double over Milan; it was also his 17th league goal of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inter.it/en/news/2020/02/10/stats-inter-4-2-milan.html|title=Milano is Black&Blue! The facts and figures following Inter's derby success|publisher=Inter Milan|date=10 February 2020|access-date=9 August 2020|archive-date=3 May 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210503170142/https://www.inter.it/en/news/2020/02/10/stats-inter-4-2-milan.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 25 July, Lukaku scored a brace in a 3–0 win at [[Genoa C.F.C.|Genoa]]; in doing so, he became the first Inter player since [[István Nyers]] in the 1949–50 season to score 15 away goals in a Serie A season, and the first do to so in his debut season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/lukaku-equals-serie-a-record-for-inter-after-double-in-win/|title=Lukaku equals 70-year Serie A record for Inter after double in win at Genoa|website=Goal.com|date=25 July 2020|access-date=9 August 2020|archive-date=21 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210421224550/https://www.goal.com/en/news/lukaku-equals-serie-a-record-for-inter-after-double-in-win/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sempreinter.com/2020/07/20/photo-inters-lukaku-first-player-to-score-13-away-goals-in-debut-serie-a-campaign/|title=Photo – Inter's Romelu Lukaku First Player To Score 13 Away Goals in Debut Serie A Campaign|website=Sempre Inter|date=20 July 2020|access-date=9 August 2020|archive-date=3 May 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210503170634/https://sempreinter.com/2020/07/20/photo-inters-lukaku-first-player-to-score-13-away-goals-in-debut-serie-a-campaign/|url-status=live}}</ref> He concluded his first Serie A season with 23 goals, as Inter finished runner-up by just one point to [[Juventus FC|Juventus]] in the standings; only Ronaldo (25) and Nyers (26) have scored more than him in their debut season at Inter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.football-italia.net/156356/lukaku-inter-can-do-much-better|title=Lukaku: 'Inter can do much better'|website=Football Italia|date=25 July 2020|access-date=9 August 2020|archive-date=21 April 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210421230334/https://www.football-italia.net/156356/lukaku-inter-can-do-much-better|url-status=live}}</ref> On 5 August, Lukaku scored in a 2–0 win over [[Getafe CF|Getafe]] in the Europa League's round of 16, helping his side reach the quarter-finals of a European competition for the first time since 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/0260-100f93c14bfc-4234965fda83-1000--inter-2-0-getafe-clinical-nerazzurri-make-spanish-side-pay/|title=Inter 2–0 Getafe: clinical Nerazzurri make Spanish side pay|publisher=UEFA|date=5 August 2020|access-date=9 August 2020|archive-date=9 August 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200809082709/https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/match/2028228--internazionale-vs-getafe/postmatch/report/|url-status=live}}</ref> It was his 30th goal in all competitions, a new personal best, and he had also scored for the eighth consecutive Europa League match, equalling the all-time record set by [[Alan Shearer]] in 2004–05.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sempreinter.com/2020/08/06/player-ratings-inter-2-0-getafe-romelu-lukakus-30th-goal-christian-eriksen-4th-seal-quarterfinal-place/|title=Player Ratings Inter 2 – 0 Getafe: Romelu Lukaku's 30th Goal & Christian Eriksen 4th Seal Quarterfinal Place|website=Sepmre Inter|date=6 August 2020|access-date=9 August 2020|archive-date=3 May 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210503165648/https://sempreinter.com/2020/08/06/player-ratings-inter-2-0-getafe-romelu-lukakus-30th-goal-christian-eriksen-4th-seal-quarterfinal-place/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inter.it/en/news/2020/08/09/inter-bayer-leverkusen-stats-and-trivia.html|title=Inter vs. Bayer Leverkusen, stats and trivia|publisher=Inter Milan|date=6 August 2020|access-date=9 August 2020|archive-date=20 September 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200920142008/https://www.inter.it/en/news/2020/08/09/inter-bayer-leverkusen-stats-and-trivia.html|url-status=live}}</ref> In the quarter-finals on 10 August, he broke this record, scoring in his ninth consecutive match in the competition in a 2–1 victory over [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]] in Düsseldorf, to send Inter into the semi-finals.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football-italia.net/157064/lukaku-barella-man-match |title=Lukaku: 'Barella man of the match' |website=football-italia.net |date=10 August 2020 |access-date=11 August 2020 |archive-date=1 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201001010729/https://www.football-italia.net/157064/lukaku-barella-man-match |url-status=live }}</ref> On 17 August, Lukaku scored a brace in a 5–0 win against [[FC Shakhtar Donetsk|Shakhtar Donetsk]] — his tenth consecutive match in the competition — as Inter reached the [[2020 UEFA Europa League Final|final]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/53759741 |title=Inter Milan 5–0 Shakhtar Donetsk |website=BBC Sport |date=17 August 2020 |access-date=17 August 2020 |archive-date=20 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210220203526/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/53759741 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the final, he earned and scored a penalty in the fifth minute, but also scored an own goal in the 74th minute, which was eventually the winning goal for Sevilla in a 3–2 defeat.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jackson|first=Jamie|date=21 August 2020|title=Sevilla win sixth Europa League trophy after own goal from Inter's Lukaku|newspaper=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/aug/21/internazionale-sevilla-europa-league-final-match-report|access-date=22 August 2020|issn=0261-3077|archive-date=29 March 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210329213734/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/aug/21/internazionale-sevilla-europa-league-final-match-report|url-status=live}}</ref> Lukaku equalled Ronaldo's record in 1997–98 season, by scoring 34 goals in all competitions.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20200822-sevilla-beat-inter-in-thrilling-3-2-struggle-to-win-europa-league |title=Sevilla beat Inter in thrilling 3–2 struggle to win Europa League |publisher=France 24 |date=22 August 2020 |access-date=27 August 2020 |archive-date=1 May 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210501214143/https://www.france24.com/en/20200822-sevilla-beat-inter-in-thrilling-3-2-struggle-to-win-europa-league |url-status=live }}</ref>

====2020–21: Serie A champion====
On 21 October 2020, Lukaku scored a brace in a 2–2 draw against [[Borussia Mönchengladbach]] in the first match of the [[2020–21 UEFA Champions League]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/54559786 |title=Inter Milan 2–2 Borussia Monchengladbach |website=BBC Sport |date=21 October 2020 |access-date=22 October 2020 |archive-date=28 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201028000531/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/54559786 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 1 December, he scored another brace against Mönchengladbach to secure a 3–2 away win.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/55134435 |title=Borussia Mönchengladbach 2–3 Inter Milan |website=BBC Sport |date=1 December 2020 |access-date=1 December 2020 |archive-date=6 December 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201206081551/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/55134435 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, Inter drew their last match against Shakhtar Donetsk, to finish last in their group, and were eliminated from all European competitions.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.givemesport.com/1626377-inter-milan-crash-out-of-champions-league-after-romelu-lukaku-accidentally-blocks-winner |title=Inter Milan crash out of Champions League after Romelu Lukaku accidentally blocks winner |website=GiveMeSport |date=9 December 2020 |access-date=10 December 2020 |archive-date=9 December 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201209222544/https://www.givemesport.com/1626377-inter-milan-crash-out-of-champions-league-after-romelu-lukaku-accidentally-blocks-winner |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 3 January 2021, Lukaku scored in a 6–2 win over [[F.C. Crotone|Crotone]], to reach his 50th goal across all competitions in only 70 matches, breaking the previous record of Ronaldo who scored fifty goals in 77 matches.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.caughtoffside.com/2021/01/03/lukaku-breaks-ronaldo-inter-milan-record/ |title=Romelu Lukaku breaks Ronaldo record for Inter Milan with stunning stats |website=CaughtOffside |date=3 January 2021 |access-date=4 January 2021 |archive-date=3 May 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210503170229/https://www.caughtoffside.com/2021/01/03/lukaku-breaks-ronaldo-inter-milan-record/ |url-status=live }}</ref> On 26 January, Lukaku was involved in a confrontation with former Manchester United teammate [[Zlatan Ibrahimović]] in Inter's [[2020–21 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]] quarter-final match against Milan. Following a foul committed by Lukaku late in the first half, he and Ibrahimović could be heard exchanging insults as the pair clashed heads, and had to be restrained by their respective teammates. Both players were booked as their arguments continued into the tunnel at half-time. Ibrahimović would be sent off during the second half following a second yellow for a foul on [[Aleksandar Kolarov]], as Inter went on to record a 2–1 victory.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11854/12199921/zlatan-ibrahimovic-and-romelu-lukaku-clash-in-milan-derby |title=Zlatan Ibrahimovic and Romelu Lukaku clash in Milan derby |website=Sky Sports |date=27 January 2021 |access-date=31 January 2021 |archive-date=7 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210207132332/https://www.skysports.com/amp/football/news/11854/12199921/zlatan-ibrahimovic-and-romelu-lukaku-clash-in-milan-derby |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 14 February, he scored a brace and got an assist against [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]] in a 3–1 victory, bringing his Serie A tally to 16 goals for the season, and equalling Cristiano Ronaldo as the league's top scorer. Lukaku's second goal was also the 300th of his professional career.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/56065773 |title=Inter Milan 3–1 Lazio |website=BBC Sport |date=14 February 2021 |access-date=14 February 2021 |archive-date=5 May 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210505223333/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/56065773 |url-status=live }}</ref> Inter won the [[2020–21 Serie A]] for the first time since the [[2009–10 Serie A|2009–10]] season.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/56964913|title=Inter Milan: Italian giants win first Serie A for 11 years|website=BBC Sport|date=2 May 2021|access-date=2 May 2021|archive-date=3 August 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210803205004/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/56964913|url-status=live}}</ref> Lukaku finished the season 2020–21 with 24 league goals, eleven assists - making him the top scorer on the title-winning team and the second top-scorer in the league, behind Ronaldo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://footballexpress.in/romelu-lukaku-to-stay-at-inter-milan-next-season/|title=Romelu Lukaku to stay at Inter Milan next season|website=Football Express|date=3 June 2021|access-date=3 June 2021|archive-date=5 June 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210605034321/https://footballexpress.in/romelu-lukaku-to-stay-at-inter-milan-next-season/|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Return to Chelsea===
====2021–22: FIFA Club World Cup champion and loss of form====
[[File:Lukaku 2021.jpg|thumb|upright|Lukaku playing for Chelsea in 2021]]

On 12 August 2021, Lukaku returned to his former club Chelsea on a five-year deal, a decade after he had originally joined the club, for a reported club record fee of £97.5&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Chelsea re-sign Lukaku for club record £97.5m|website=BBC Sport|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58111490|access-date=12 August 2021|archive-date=13 August 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210813080940/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58111490|url-status=live}}</ref> In making the move, Lukaku became the most expensive player of all time, with cumulative transfer fees of almost £285&nbsp;million, surpassing [[Neymar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/neymar-romelu-lukaku-paris-st-germain-belgian-manchester-united-b1901685.html|title=Chelsea return moves Romelu Lukaku ahead of Neymar as most expensive player ever|last=White|first=Tom|newspaper=The Independent|date=12 August 2021|access-date=16 August 2021|archive-date=16 August 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210816224554/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/neymar-romelu-lukaku-paris-st-germain-belgian-manchester-united-b1901685.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Lukaku admitted in an interview that he did request Inter to reach to an agreement with Chelsea, stating: "I didn't want to go behind Inter's back. They got me out of the shit. I was in a deep hole at Manchester United. After training I went to [head coach Simone] Inzaghi's office. I didn't want to ruin the atmosphere because I was no longer with my head in Milan. So I asked him: please find an agreement."<ref>{{Cite web |title=Romelu Lukaku reveals how Chelsea's persistence turned his head this summer |url=https://weaintgotnohistory.sbnation.com/2021/9/4/22657148/romelu-lukaku-explains-how-chelseas-persistence-turned-his-head-this-summer |date=5 September 2021 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20210905034005/https://weaintgotnohistory.sbnation.com/2021/9/4/22657148/romelu-lukaku-explains-how-chelseas-persistence-turned-his-head-this-summer |archive-date=5 September 2021 |last=Pasztor |first=David |website=weaintgotnohistory.sbnation.com}}</ref>

On 22 August, Lukaku scored on his second debut in the 15th minute, converting [[Reece James (footballer, born 1999)|Reece James]]' cross, in a 2–0 away win over Arsenal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/58193457|title=Arsenal 0-2 Chelsea: Romelu Lukaku scores as Blues win|work=BBC Sport|access-date=22 August 2021|archive-date=22 August 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210822112913/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/58193457|url-status=live}}</ref> On 12 September, Lukaku scored twice at home against [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]], the first time he had scored at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bt.com/sport/news/2021/september/romelu-lukaku-nets-first-stamford-bridge-goals-as-chelsea-see-off-aston-villa|title=Romelu Lukaku nets first Stamford Bridge goals as Chelsea see off Aston Villa|publisher=[[BT Sport]]|access-date=12 September 2021|archive-date=6 July 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220706203219/https://www.bt.com/sport/news/2021/september/romelu-lukaku-nets-first-stamford-bridge-goals-as-chelsea-see-off-aston-villa|url-status=live}}</ref> Two days later, Lukaku scored his first European goal for Chelsea, against [[FC Zenit Saint Petersburg|Zenit]] in the [[2021–22 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Match report: Chelsea 1 Zenit St Petersburg 0 |url=https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/2021/09/14/match-report--chelsea-v-zenit-st-petersburg |access-date=15 September 2021 |publisher=Chelsea F.C. |archive-date=15 September 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210915080826/https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/2021/09/14/match-report--chelsea-v-zenit-st-petersburg |url-status=live }}</ref> On 8 October, Lukaku was one of five Chelsea players included in the final 30-man shortlist for the 2021 [[Ballon d'Or]], eventually finishing twelfth.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.si.com/soccer/chelsea/news/official-five-chelsea-players-among-30-man-ballon-dor-shortlist|title=Official: Azpilicueta, Kante, Jorginho, Mount & Lukaku Among Chelsea Players On 30-Man 2021 Ballon d'Or Shortlist|magazine=Sports Illustrated|date=8 October 2021|accessdate=8 October 2021|archive-date=8 October 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211008164451/https://www.si.com/soccer/chelsea/news/official-five-chelsea-players-among-30-man-ballon-dor-shortlist|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Messi wins record seventh Ballon d'Or|work=BBC Sport|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/59454640|access-date=6 January 2022|archive-date=2 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211202042954/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/59454640|url-status=live}}</ref>

In late December, Lukaku stoked controversy when during an interview with Sky Italia, he reported being "not happy" with the situation at Chelsea, and that head coach [[Thomas Tuchel]] "has chosen to play with another system", comparing the teams tactics with that at Inter. In the same interview, he went on to express his wish to return to Inter "in the near future".<ref>{{Cite web|date=30 December 2021|title=Lukaku 'not happy' with Chelsea situation as problems mount for Tuchel|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2021/dec/30/lukaku-not-happy-with-chelsea-situation-as-problems-mount-for-tuchel|access-date=6 January 2022|last=Dobson|first=Mark|website=The Guardian|archive-date=6 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220106075127/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2021/dec/30/lukaku-not-happy-with-chelsea-situation-as-problems-mount-for-tuchel|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Lukaku 'not happy' with Chelsea role|work=BBC Sport|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/59833820|access-date=6 January 2022|archive-date=6 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220106234847/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/59833820|url-status=live}}</ref> Consequently, Tuchel dropped him from the squad altogether for a match against title challengers Liverpool, which ended 2–2.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Chelsea come from two down to deny Liverpool in thriller|work=BBC Sport|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/59792567|access-date=6 January 2022|archive-date=5 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220105055504/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/59792567|url-status=live}}</ref> After then holding talks with Tuchel, Lukaku issued an apology, saying: "I'm sorry for the upset I have caused", and stated that he "wanted to move forward".<ref>{{Cite web|title=Exclusive Romelu Lukaku interview: I'm sorry for the upset I have caused|work=ChelseaFC |url=https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/2022/01/04/exclusive-romelu-lukaku-interview|access-date=6 January 2022|publisher=Chelsea FC|archive-date=5 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220105073300/https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/2022/01/04/exclusive-romelu-lukaku-interview|url-status=live}}</ref> He was restored to the first team and started in the first leg of the EFL Cup semi-final win against Tottenham Hotspur, but was fined for his comments.<ref>{{Cite web|date=4 January 2022|title=Tuchel fines Lukaku over Chelsea 'mess' despite striker's apology for interview|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2022/jan/04/chelsea-lukaku-sorry-clean-mess-up-tuchel|last=Steinberg|first=Jacob|access-date=6 January 2022|website=The Guardian|archive-date=5 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220105232921/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2022/jan/04/chelsea-lukaku-sorry-clean-mess-up-tuchel|url-status=live}}</ref> Lukaku finished the season having scored eight goals in 26 league games; he was judged by ESPN to be the worst signing of the Premier League season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/english-premier-league/story/4656121/premier-leagues-10-best-and-worst-transfers-of-the-season |title=Premier League season's 10 best and worst transfers |last=Darke |first=Ian |date=4 May 2022 |publisher=ESPN |access-date=17 August 2022 |archive-date=17 August 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220817114835/https://www.espn.co.uk/football/english-premier-league/story/4656121/premier-leagues-10-best-and-worst-transfers-of-the-season |url-status=live }}</ref>

====2022–23: Return to Inter Milan on loan and Champions League runner-up====
On 29 June 2022, Chelsea announced that Lukaku would return to Inter for a season-long loan for the 2022–23 campaign.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lukaku loan confirmed|url=https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/2022/06/29/lukaku-loan-confirmed|access-date=29 June 2022|publisher=Chelsea F.C.|archive-date=29 June 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220629182616/https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/2022/06/29/lukaku-loan-confirmed|url-status=live}}</ref> It was reported that they had agreed to pay a loan fee of approximately €8&nbsp;million (£6.9&nbsp;million), and that Lukaku took a pay cut.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Chelsea's Lukaku completes loan move to Inter Milan |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/61908384 |access-date=29 June 2022 |archive-date=20 September 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230920015007/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/61908384 |url-status=live }}</ref> He would choose to wear the number 90 shirt, due to number 9 being already used by [[Edin Džeko]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Calciomercato/Inter/29-06-2022/ora-ufficio-lukaku-inter-duetto-zhang-4401203624605.shtml|title=Now it's official: Lukaku is from Inter, he will have the number 90 shirt. And it's immediately a duet on the terrace with Zhang!|date=29 June 2022|access-date=29 June 2022|archive-date=20 October 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231020041613/https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Calciomercato/Inter/29-06-2022/ora-ufficio-lukaku-inter-duetto-zhang-4401203624605.shtml|url-status=live}}</ref> On 13 August, he scored his first goal since his return to the ''Nerazzurri'' in a 2–1 win over [[US Lecce|Lecce]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Serie-A/Inter/13-08-2022/lecce-inter-1-2-gol-lukaku-dumfries-partita-4401862121739.shtml|title=Inter at their last gasp in Lecce: Dumfries scores in the 95th minute! Lukaku, return with goal|date=13 August 2022|access-date=14 October 2023|archive-date=2 September 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230902094115/https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Serie-A/Inter/13-08-2022/lecce-inter-1-2-gol-lukaku-dumfries-partita-4401862121739.shtml|url-status=live}}</ref>

After various injuries in the first months of the season,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Serie-A/Inter/28-08-2022/ahia-inter-si-fatto-male-lukaku-saltera-derby-ed-dubbio-il-bayern-4402076440607.shtml|title=Ouch Inter, Lukaku got hurt! He will miss the derby and is in doubt for Bayern|date=28 August 2023|access-date=14 October 2023|archive-date=2 September 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230902093721/https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Serie-A/Inter/28-08-2022/ahia-inter-si-fatto-male-lukaku-saltera-derby-ed-dubbio-il-bayern-4402076440607.shtml|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Serie-A/Inter/31-10-2022/lukaku-altro-infortunio-coscia-tempi-recupero-450892726719.shtml|title=Lukaku, new injury: he won't be there against Juve|date=31 October 2023|access-date=14 October 2023|archive-date=19 January 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230119190304/https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Serie-A/Inter/31-10-2022/lukaku-altro-infortunio-coscia-tempi-recupero-450892726719.shtml|url-status=live}}</ref> Lukaku made his first start for Inter in a 1–0 over championship leaders Napoli, giving them their first league defeat for the 2022–23 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/napoli-invincible-dzeko-inter-serie-a/blt54557050e15206f1|title=Napoli no longer invincible! Dzeko fires Inter to vital win over previously unbeaten Serie A leaders|publisher=Goal.com|author=Peter McVitie|date=4 January 2023|access-date=4 January 2023|archive-date=5 January 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230105025808/https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/napoli-invincible-dzeko-inter-serie-a/blt54557050e15206f1|url-status=live}}</ref> Fourteen days later, despite featuring on the bench, following a 3–0 win over Milan, he won the [[2022 Supercoppa Italiana]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://football-italia.net/supercoppa-italiana-milan-0-3-inter-dominant-derby-della-madonnina/|title=SUPERCOPPA ITALIANA / MILAN 0-3 INTER: DOMINANT DERBY DELLA MADONNINA|publisher=Football Italia|author=Susy Campanale|date=18 January 2023|access-date=18 January 2023|archive-date=19 January 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230119014220/https://football-italia.net/supercoppa-italiana-milan-0-3-inter-dominant-derby-della-madonnina/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="MOTM">{{cite web|url=https://www.legaseriea.it/it/media/supercoppa-frecciarossa/edin-dzeko-e-l-ea-sports-man-of-the-match|title=Edin Dzeko è l'EA Sports man of the match|trans-title=Edin Dzeko is EA Sports man of the match|website=legaseriea.it|date=18 January 2023|access-date=18 January 2023|language=it|archive-date=18 January 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230118214437/https://www.legaseriea.it/it/media/supercoppa-frecciarossa/edin-dzeko-e-l-ea-sports-man-of-the-match|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 22 February, in the first leg of [[2022–23 UEFA Champions League#Round-of-16|Champions League round-of-16]], he scored the only goal of a home win over [[FC Porto|Porto]], which led Inter to advance to quarter-finals, after securing a away draw in Porto.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/it/liste/inter-porto-cronaca-tabellino-pagelle-voti/blt7ab7f2ef14f27f4d|title=Inter-Porto 1-0: Lukaku comes in and solves it, the first round is Nerazzurri|author=Marco Trombetta|website=Goal.com|date=22 February 2023|access-date=23 February 2023|archive-date=23 February 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230223082903/https://www.goal.com/it/liste/inter-porto-cronaca-tabellino-pagelle-voti/blt7ab7f2ef14f27f4d|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/it/notizie/inter-riecco-lukaku-in-goal-in-serie-a-189-giorni-dopo/bltbb980d90cb9d7e8f|title=Inter, Lukaku returns as protagonist: decisive also in the Champions League|website=Goal.com|date=22 February 2023|access-date=23 February 2023|archive-date=23 February 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230223082908/https://www.goal.com/it/notizie/inter-riecco-lukaku-in-goal-in-serie-a-189-giorni-dopo/bltbb980d90cb9d7e8f|url-status=live}}</ref> He would start to regain his form on the latter months of the season, netting six goals in six appearances between April and May. On 5 April, he urged Serie A to take action, after he was racially abused during a [[Coppa Italia]] draw at [[Juventus FC|Juventus]].<ref>{{cite news |date=5 April 2023 |title=Inter's Romelu Lukaku demands action after racist abuse at Juventus |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/apr/05/romelu-lukaku-inter-demands-serie-a-action-racist-abuse-juventus |access-date=5 April 2023 |issn=0261-3077 |archive-date=5 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230405141038/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/apr/05/romelu-lukaku-inter-demands-serie-a-action-racist-abuse-juventus |url-status=live }}</ref> On 24 May, he won his first [[Coppa Italia]], as Inter defeated [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]] 2–1 in the final.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Coppa-Italia/24-05-2023/inter-vince-coppa-italia-2-1-fiorentina-doppietta-lautaro-4601738135825.shtml|title=Monstrous Lautaro, Fiorentina overturned: the Italian Cup belongs to Inter!|date=24 May 2023|access-date=14 October 2023|archive-date=31 May 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230531220155/https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Coppa-Italia/24-05-2023/inter-vince-coppa-italia-2-1-fiorentina-doppietta-lautaro-4601738135825.shtml|url-status=live}}</ref> On 10 June, he played in the [[2023 UEFA Champions League final|2023 Champions League final]] against Manchester City, but he was criticized for his performance in the game, missing a number of key chances after coming off the bench during the second half, as his side suffered a 1–0 defeat.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://football-italia.net/lukaku-falls-short-in-quest-for-inter-redemption-in-ucl-final/|title=Lukaku falls short in quest for Inter redemption in UCL final|website=Football Italia|date=10 June 2023|access-date=10 June 2023|archive-date=10 June 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230610213535/https://football-italia.net/lukaku-falls-short-in-quest-for-inter-redemption-in-ucl-final/|url-status=live}}</ref>

====2023–24: Loan to Roma====
During the summer of 2023, Lukaku was reportedly negotiating with Inter Milan [[Derby d'Italia|rivals]] Juventus for a possible move, enraging many Inter and Juventus fans.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Horncastle |first=James |date=5 August 2023 |title=Romelu Lukaku to Juventus? With him, in a transfer window, anything can happen |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4748567/2023/08/05/romelu-lukaku-chelsea-juventus-inter/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230806164050/https://theathletic.com/4748567/2023/08/05/romelu-lukaku-chelsea-juventus-inter/ |archive-date=6 August 2023 |access-date=16 January 2024 |work=[[The Athletic]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Watson |first=Fraser |date=9 August 2023 |title=Juventus ultras unfurl brutal Romelu Lukaku banner as Chelsea swap deal put in doubt |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/juventus-romelu-lukaku-chelsea-transfer-30668278 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231021060559/https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/juventus-romelu-lukaku-chelsea-transfer-30668278.amp |archive-date=21 October 2023 |access-date=16 January 2024 |work=[[Daily Mirror]]}}</ref> However, on 31 August 2023, Lukaku was sent to another Serie A club, [[AS Roma|Roma]],<ref>{{Cite news|title=Romelu Lukaku is a Giallarossi player!|website=AS Roma|url=https://www.asroma.com/en/news/69316/romelu-lukaku-is-a-giallorossi-player|date=31 August 2023|access-date=31 August 2023|archive-date=31 August 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230831100636/https://www.asroma.com/en/news/69316/romelu-lukaku-is-a-giallorossi-player|url-status=live}}</ref> on a season-long loan deal for a reported fee in the region of £8&nbsp;million (€9.3&nbsp;million), with the club covering the whole of the player's salary.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Romano |first=Fabrizio |author-link=Fabrizio Romano |title=Roma agree £8m season-long loan deal with Chelsea for Romelu Lukaku |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/28/roma-agree-season-long-loan-deal-chelsea-romelu-lukaku |date=31 August 2023 |access-date=31 August 2023 |archive-date=18 September 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230918020257/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/28/roma-agree-season-long-loan-deal-chelsea-romelu-lukaku |url-status=live }}</ref> Lukaku also reportedly agreed to a new contract at Chelsea, which included a wage cut to the remainder of his contract and a release clause of £37&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Law |first=Matt |title=Roma agree £8m season-long loan deal with Chelsea for Romelu Lukaku |work=The Telegraph |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2023/08/28/chelsea-transfer-news-romelu-lukaku-roma-loan-agreed/ |date=28 August 2023 |access-date=31 August 2023 |archive-date=31 August 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230831210119/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2023/08/28/chelsea-transfer-news-romelu-lukaku-roma-loan-agreed/ |url-status=live }}</ref> On 1 September, he made his debut for Roma at [[Stadio Olimpico]], coming off the bench in a 2–1 defeat against Milan.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/ten-man-milan-grab-2-1-win-roma-2023-09-01/ |title=Ten-man Milan grab 2-1 win at Roma as Lukaku makes debut |publisher=Reuters |date=2 September 2023 |access-date=17 September 2023 |archive-date=20 September 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230920172720/https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/ten-man-milan-grab-2-1-win-roma-2023-09-01/ |url-status=live }}</ref> On 17 September, he scored his first goal in a 7–0 win over [[Empoli FC|Empoli]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eurosport.it/calcio/serie-a/2023-2024/roma-empoli-7-0-giallorossi-dominanti.-doppietta-di-dybala-prime-gioie-per-lukaku-e-sanches_sto9801640/story.shtml |title=Roma-Empoli 7-0: giallorossi dominanti. Doppietta di Dybala, prime gioie per Lukaku e Sanches |publisher=Eurosport |language=it |date=17 September 2023 |access-date=17 September 2023 |archive-date=30 October 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231030223541/https://www.eurosport.it/geoblocking.shtml |url-status=live }}</ref>

===Napoli===
On 29 August 2024, Lukaku permanently transferred to Serie A club [[SSC Napoli|Napoli]] for a fee reportedly worth €30 million.<ref>{{cite web |title=Lukaku lands in Italy to finalise move to Napoli and rekindle winning relationship with Conte |url=https://apnews.com/article/lukaku-conte-napoli-serie-a-2915196e6725702705fd87610717dea0 |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=29 August 2024 |date=28 August 2024 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Il Napoli ufficializza l'acquisto di Romelu Lukaku |url=https://sscnapoli.it/il-napoli-ufficializza-lacquisto-di-romelu-lukaku/ |publisher=SSC Napoli |access-date=29 August 2024 |language=Italian |date=29 August 2024 }}</ref> On his debut for the club two days later, he scored an equaliser in stoppage time of an eventual 2–1 win over [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Lukaku late show helps save Napoli |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2492795/lukaku-late-show-helps-save-napoli |work=The Express Tribune |access-date=2 September 2024 |date=2 September 2024}}</ref>  On 23 May 2025, he scored Napoli's second goal against [[Cagliari Calcio|Cagliari]] as they won 2–0 to secure the club's fourth Serie A title.<ref name="CBS">{{cite web |title=Napoli down Cagliari, win 2024-25 Serie A title: Antonio Conte wins the Scudetto in his first year at the club |url=https://www.cbssports.com/soccer/news/napoli-down-cagliari-win-2024-25-serie-a-title-antonio-conte-wins-the-scudetto-in-his-first-year-at-the-club/|first=Francesco |last=Porzio|work=CBS Sports |access-date=23 May 2025|date=23 May 2025}}</ref> During the 2025–26 pre-season, Lukaku sustained a left thigh injury which would sideline him for several months.<ref>{{cite web |title=Napoli's Lukaku sidelined with thigh injury, may need surgery |url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/napolis-lukaku-sidelined-with-thigh-injury-may-need-surgery-2025-08-18/ |publisher=Reuters |date=18 August 2025}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Lukaku returns to Belgium, decides against surgery on thigh injury |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/article/lukaku-returns-belgium-decides-against-113000685.html |publisher=Yahoo Sports |access-date=12 October 2025 |date=10 October 2025}}</ref>

==International career==
===2008–2017: Youth level and early international career===
[[File:Lukaku Belgium National Team vs USA 2013 (cropped).jpg|thumb|145px|left|Lukaku with [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]] in 2013]]

Lukaku was a member of the [[Belgium national under-21 football team|Belgium under-21 team]] and scored a goal on his debut against [[Slovenia national under-21 football team|Slovenia]]. On 24 February 2010, Lukaku was named for the first time in the [[Belgium national football team|Belgium senior squad]] for a [[Friendly (association football)|friendly]] against [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dhnet.be/sports/diables-rouges/article/301782/romelu-lukaku-est-officiellement-diable-rouge.html#video15 |title=Romelu Lukaku est officiellement Diable Rouge |newspaper=La Dernière Heure |date=24 February 2010 |access-date=17 November 2010 |language=fr |archive-date=1 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100901183352/http://www.dhnet.be/sports/diables-rouges/article/301782/romelu-lukaku-est-officiellement-diable-rouge.html#video15 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 17 November 2010, he scored his first two international goals in a friendly against [[Russia national football team|Russia]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Russia vs Belgium Player Ratings|url=http://www.goal.com/en-us/match/54146/russia-vs-belgium/report|website=Goal.com|date=17 November 2010|access-date=20 March 2012|archive-date=7 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180707011442/http://www.goal.com/en-us/match/54146/russia-vs-belgium/report|url-status=live}}</ref> Lukaku scored his first goal in almost two years for the national team, netting the winner in a 4–2 friendly victory over rivals the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] on 15 August 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.goal.com/en-us/match/80473/belgium-vs-netherlands/report |title=Belgium 4–2 Netherlands: Mertens inspires impressive win for hosts |website=Goal.com |date=15 August 2012 |access-date=5 February 2013 |archive-date=24 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624204326/http://www.goal.com/en-us/match/80473/belgium-vs-netherlands/report |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 11 October 2013, Lukaku scored two goals as Belgium defeated Croatia 2–1 to secure a place in the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] finals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/world-cup/10374055/Croatia-1-Belgium-2-match-report.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/world-cup/10374055/Croatia-1-Belgium-2-match-report.html |archive-date=10 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|title=Croatia 1 Belgium 2: match report|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=11 October 2013 }}{{cbignore}}</ref> In May 2014, Lukaku was named in Belgium's squad for the 2014 World Cup. On 26 May, he scored his first international hat-trick in a pre-tournament friendly against neighbouring [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/27583281|title=Belgium 5–1 Luxembourg|date=26 May 2014|access-date=27 May 2014|website=BBC Sport|archive-date=27 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527135841/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/27583281|url-status=live}}</ref> However, as Belgium made seven substitutions during this match instead of the permitted six, it was not initially recognised as an official match by [[FIFA]].<ref name="HLN040614">{{cite web |url=http://www.hln.be/hln/nl/16076/De-Rode-Duivels/article/detail/1907260/2014/06/04/Debuut-Bossut-en-Januzaj-en-hattrick-Lukaku-zijn-ongeldig.dhtml |title=Debuut Bossut en Januzaj, én hattrick Lukaku zijn ongeldig |language=nl |newspaper=Het Laatste Nieuws |date=4 June 2014 |access-date=4 June 2014 |archive-date=3 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303180109/http://www.hln.be/hln/nl/16076/De-Rode-Duivels/article/detail/1907260/2014/06/04/Debuut-Bossut-en-Januzaj-en-hattrick-Lukaku-zijn-ongeldig.dhtml |url-status=live }}</ref> On 1 June, he scored first of Belgium's two goals in the 2–0 victory in a friendly against [[Sweden men's national football team|Sweden]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Lukaku and Hazard score in comfortable Belgium win over Sweden|url=https://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/news/world-cup-lukaku-hazard-score-comfortable-belgium-win-181057930--sow.html|website=Yahoo Eurosport UK|access-date=1 June 2014|date=1 June 2014|archive-date=2 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140602201401/https://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/news/world-cup-lukaku-hazard-score-comfortable-belgium-win-181057930--sow.html|url-status=live}}</ref> In Belgium's first match of the tournament, a 2–1 win against [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]] in [[Belo Horizonte]], Lukaku started and played 58 minutes, before being replaced by [[Divock Origi]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chowdhury|first1=Saj|title=Belgium 2–1 Algeria|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/25285127|access-date=22 June 2014|website=BBC Sport|date=17 June 2014|archive-date=26 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160126180207/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25285127|url-status=live}}</ref> In the [[2014 FIFA World Cup knockout stage#Round of 16|round of 16]], Lukaku came on as a substitute prior to [[Overtime (association football)|extra time]], and assisted [[Kevin De Bruyne]]'s opening goal three minutes later. In the 105th minute, he scored his first goal of the tournament, as Belgium defeated the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] 2–1.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/27990605|title=Belgium 2–1 USA|date=1 July 2014|access-date=2 July 2014|website=BBC Sport|archive-date=16 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151216143105/http://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/27990605|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 29 March 2016, Lukaku headed a consolation in a 2–1 loss away to [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]], assisted by his brother, [[Jordan Lukaku]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/portugal-vs-belgium/report/353945|title=Portugal 2–1 Belgium: Cristiano Ronaldo and Nani score in rescheduled game|website=Sky Sports|access-date=23 October 2020|archive-date=27 October 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201027112912/https://www.skysports.com/football/portugal-vs-belgium/report/353945|url-status=live}}</ref> At [[UEFA Euro 2016]], Lukaku scored twice in Belgium's 3–0 second group stage match win on 18 June 2016 over the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Sam |last=Wallace |title=Belgium 3 Republic of Ireland 0: Lukaku double leaves Irish needing win against Italy to progress |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2016/06/18/belgium-3-republic-of-ireland-0-lukaku-double-leaves-irish-needi/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2016/06/18/belgium-3-republic-of-ireland-0-lukaku-double-leaves-irish-needi/ |archive-date=10 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=18 June 2016 |access-date=18 June 2016}}{{cbignore}}</ref>

===2017–2018: All-time Belgium top scorer===
[[File:Bel-Tun (15).jpg|thumb|145px|right|Lukaku (right) playing for Belgium at the 2018 FIFA World Cup]]

On 10 November 2017, Lukaku equalled the all-time Belgium goalscoring record set by [[Bernard Voorhoof]] and [[Paul Van Himst]], after scoring twice against [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] in a 3–3 draw.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/29908/11121930/romelu-lukaku-equals-all-time-belgium-goalscoring-record|title=Romelu Lukaku equals all-time Belgium goalscoring record|website=Sky Sports|date=11 November 2017|access-date=12 November 2017|archive-date=19 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619140342/http://www.skysports.com/football/news/29908/11121930/romelu-lukaku-equals-all-time-belgium-goalscoring-record|url-status=live}}</ref> Four days after he equalled the record, Lukaku became Belgium's all-time record goalscorer with 31 international goals at the age of 24, after he scored the only goal in a 1–0 win over [[Japan national football team|Japan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/11/14/manchester-united-striker-romelu-lukaku-breaks-belgium-goalscoring-record-at-the-age-of-24-7079702/|title=Manchester United striker Romelu Lukaku breaks Belgium goalscoring record at the age of 24|newspaper=Metro|date=14 November 2017|access-date=15 November 2017|archive-date=15 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171115021041/http://metro.co.uk/2017/11/14/manchester-united-striker-romelu-lukaku-breaks-belgium-goalscoring-record-at-the-age-of-24-7079702/|url-status=live}}</ref> Although this record was counted by the [[Royal Belgian Football Association]],<ref name="KBVBdata">{{cite web|url=http://www.belgianfootball.be/nl/alle-rode-duivels|title=Alle Rode Duivels|publisher=Royal Belgian Football Association|language=nl|access-date=17 November 2017|archive-date=17 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017041005/http://www.belgianfootball.be/nl/alle-rode-duivels|url-status=live}}</ref> FIFA initially only officially recognised 28 goals, after a nullified international friendly against Luxembourg on 26 May 2014, where he netted a hat trick in a 5–1 win, because the former Belgium coach, [[Marc Wilmots]] made seven substitutions during the match instead of the permitted six, which are not in accordance to the [[Laws of the Game (association football)|laws of the game]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/belgium/story/3271412/fifa-doesnt-recognise-romelu-lukaku-all-time-goals-record-for-belgium|title=FIFA doesn't recognise Romelu Lukaku all-time goals record for Belgium|website=ESPN FC|date=15 November 2017|access-date=16 November 2017|archive-date=16 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171116002819/http://www.espnfc.com/belgium/story/3271412/fifa-doesnt-recognise-romelu-lukaku-all-time-goals-record-for-belgium|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/fifa-not-recognise-romelu-lukaku-11526611|title=Why FIFA does not recognise Romelu Lukaku as Belgium's all-time record goal scorer despite him netting his 31st|newspaper=Daily Mirror|date=15 November 2017|access-date=15 November 2017|archive-date=19 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619141734/https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/fifa-not-recognise-romelu-lukaku-11526611|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2023, FIFA recognizes the three matches from 2012, 2014 and 2017 in their [[List of men's footballers with 100 or more international caps|FIFA Century Club]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=FIFA Century Club |url=https://digitalhub.fifa.com/m/7a29d8a2cac79416/original/Century-Club-01112021.pdf }}</ref>

On 6 June 2018, Lukaku officially became Belgium's all-time leading scorer with 31 goals, after scoring a goal in a 3–0 win over [[Egypt national football team|Egypt]]. He also broke a three-way tie with the previous record goalscorers, Bernard Voorhoof and Paul Van Himst.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/report?gameId=508389|title=Romelu Lukaku becomes Belgium's all-time leading scorer in win vs. Egypt|publisher=ESPN|date=6 June 2018|access-date=8 June 2018|archive-date=10 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180810223018/http://www.espn.com/soccer/report?gameId=508389|url-status=live}}</ref>

===2018–2022: Belgium's Golden Generation===
[[File:Romelu Lukaku (12.06.2021) (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|268x268px|upright|Lukaku playing for Belgium in 2021]]

On 18 June, Lukaku scored twice in a 3–0 win over [[Panama national football team|Panama]] in their opening group game at the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |title=World Cup 2018: Belgium best debutants Panama 3–0 in Sochi |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44434275 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=19 June 2018 |archive-date=28 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181128030324/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44434275 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the next group game on 23 June 2018, he scored twice again in a 5–2 win over [[Tunisia national football team|Tunisia]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44439152|title=World Cup 2018: Belgium v Tunisia|date=23 June 2018|website=BBC Sport|access-date=23 June 2018|language=en-GB|archive-date=22 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622205012/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44439152|url-status=live}}</ref> In doing so, Lukaku became the first player since [[Diego Maradona]] in 1986 to score two goals or more in consecutive World Cup matches.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en/amp/news/lukaku-makes-world-cup-history-for-belgium/jozzix6p5v02znjc8jldvfkt|title=Red-hot Lukaku makes World Cup history for Belgium|agency=goal|access-date=23 June 2018|archive-date=23 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623170312/http://www.goal.com/en/amp/news/lukaku-makes-world-cup-history-for-belgium/jozzix6p5v02znjc8jldvfkt|url-status=live}}</ref> He eventually ended the tournament with four goals and one assist, which earned him the Bronze Boot award, as Belgium finished the tournament in third place.<ref name="bronze boot"/>

On 10 October 2019, Lukaku scored his 50th and 51st international goals in a 9–0 home win over [[San Marino national football team|San Marino]], in a [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying|Euro 2020 qualifier]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/report?gameId=528939 |title=Belgium qualify for Euro 2020 with nine-goal onslaught against San Marino |publisher=ESPN |date=10 October 2019 |access-date=13 October 2019 |archive-date=12 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191012192515/https://www.espn.com/soccer/report?gameId=528939 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 12 June 2021, Lukaku scored twice in Belgium's opening group match of [[UEFA Euro 2020]], a 3–0 win over Russia.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro-2020/match/2024450--belgium-vs-russia/postmatch/report/ |title=Belgium 3-0 Russia: Lukaku scores twice in opening win |publisher=UEFA |date=12 June 2021 |access-date=23 June 2021 |archive-date=21 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210621183042/https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro-2020/match/2024450--belgium-vs-russia/postmatch/report/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> On 21 June, he scored the last goal in a 2–0 win over [[Finland national football team|Finland]] in his team's final group match.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2021/jun/21/finland-belgium-euro-2020-match-report |title=Romelu Lukaku seals Belgium win to leave Finland on the brink of exit |newspaper=The Guardian |date=21 June 2021 |access-date=23 June 2021 |archive-date=22 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210622201822/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2021/jun/21/finland-belgium-euro-2020-match-report |url-status=live }}</ref> On 2 July, he scored Belgium's only goal of the match from a penalty late in the first half in a 2–1 defeat to [[Italy national football team|Italy]] in the quarter-finals of the competition.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51198657 |title=Italy edge Belgium to set up Spain semi |website=BBC Sport |last1=Begley |first1=Emlyn |date=2 July 2021 |access-date=2 July 2021 |archive-date=9 July 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210709205723/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51198657 |url-status=live }}</ref> Two days after the final Lukaku was awarded as sole Belgian player with a selection for the UEFA Euro 2020 Team of the Tournament. He got the striker position.<ref>{{Cite web|last=UEFA.com|date=13 July 2021|title=UEFA EURO 2020 Team of the Tournament revealed|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro-2020/news/026b-12be97f0eb56-3ce3b8794fa7-1000--uefa-euro-2020-team-of-the-tournament-revealed/|access-date=23 July 2021|publisher=UEFA|archive-date=17 July 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210717051426/https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro-2020/news/026b-12be97f0eb56-3ce3b8794fa7-1000--uefa-euro-2020-team-of-the-tournament-revealed/|url-status=dead}}</ref>

Lukaku made his 100th Belgium appearance on 5 September 2021 against the Czech Republic, scoring his 67th goal in the process.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58458390|title=Lukaku marks 100th cap with 67th goal|work=BBC Sport|access-date=12 September 2021|archive-date=12 September 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210912231514/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58458390|url-status=live}}</ref>

In November 2022, he was named in the 26-man squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] in Qatar.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rbfa.be/en/news/roberto-martinez-selects-26-devils-world-cup |title=Roberto Martinez selects 26 Devils for the World Cup |publisher=[[Royal Belgian Football Association]] |date=10 November 2022 |access-date=10 November 2022 |archive-date=10 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221110120807/https://www.rbfa.be/en/news/roberto-martinez-selects-26-devils-world-cup |url-status=live }}</ref> In the final group stage match, Belgium were only a point behind Croatia, who they were playing, and needed to win in order to advance to the knockouts. Lukaku missed four clear chances in front of goal to score in a 0–0 draw, which eliminated Belgium from the tournament as they finished third in their group.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/croatia-vs-belgium/report/463002|title=World Cup 2022 – Croatia 0–0 Belgium: Romelu Lukaku misses big chances as Roberto Martinez's 'golden generation' knocked out and Croatia reach last 16|website=Sky Sports|access-date=30 June 2023|archive-date=20 December 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221220024549/https://www.skysports.com/football/croatia-vs-belgium/report/463002|url-status=live}}</ref>

===2023–present===
During [[UEFA Euro 2024 qualifying|qualifying]] for [[UEFA Euro 2024]], Lukaku scored 14 goals in eight appearances, breaking the record for goals scored by a player in a [[UEFA European Championship|European Championship]] qualifying campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/european-qualifiers/news/0253-0d80578af302-67dcd0042fc2-1000--lukaku-sets-new-european-qualifiers-scoring-record/|title=Lukaku sets new European Qualifiers scoring record|date=19 November 2023|website=UEFA}}</ref> On 28 May 2024, he was selected in the 25-man squad for the Euro 2024.<ref>{{cite news |date=28 May 2024 |title=25 Devils go to EURO 2024 |url=https://www.rbfa.be/en/news/25-devils-go-euro-2024 |publisher=Royal Belgian Football Association |access-date=28 May 2024}}</ref> On 17 June, he was denied two goals by [[Video assistant referee|VAR]] in the opening match against [[Slovakia national football team|Slovakia]], which ended in a 1–0 defeat.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hunter |first=Laura |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/17250/13151973/euro-2024-belgium-0-1-slovakia-romelu-lukaku-denied-twice-by-var-as-red-devils-suffer-shock-defeat-in-group-e-opener |title=Euro 2024 - Belgium 0-1 Slovakia: Romelu Lukaku denied twice by VAR as Red Devils suffer shock defeat in Group E opener |publisher=Sky Sports |date=18 June 2024 }}</ref>

==Style of play==
Lukaku is a left-footed player,<ref>{{cite news |last=Veysey |first=Wayne |date=6 August 2011 |url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/755/europe/2011/08/06/2309519/meet-romelu-lukaku-the-chelsea-bound-belgian-starlet-who |title=Meet Romelu Lukaku: The Chelsea-bound Belgian starlet who idolises Didier Drogba |website=Goal.com |access-date=24 December 2014 |archive-date=15 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180715035835/http://www.goal.com/en/news/755/europe/2011/08/06/2309519/meet-romelu-lukaku-the-chelsea-bound-belgian-starlet-who |url-status=live }}</ref> who in 2014 was named by ''The Guardian'' as one of the ten most promising young players in Europe. A large and physically powerful striker from an early age, with an eye for goal, Lukaku has been known to use his physicality to get around defenders.<ref name=punches/><ref name="top10list" /> However, despite his size, strength, physical build and ability to hold-up play with his back to goal, his favoured role is not as a [[Forward (association football)#Centre-forward|target-man in the centre]], but as an out-and-out [[Striker (association football)|striker]] or poacher; due to his tactical versatility, he is also capable of playing as a [[Winger (association football)|winger]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/10/04/ranking-20-best-players-premier-league-september-2017/5-romelu-lukaku/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2017/10/04/ranking-20-best-players-premier-league-september-2017/5-romelu-lukaku/ |archive-date=10 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |title=Ranking the 20 best players in the Premier League: September 2017 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=4 October 2017 |access-date=31 July 2019 }}{{cbignore}}</ref> A well-rounded [[Forward (association football)|forward]], who is also strong in the air, beyond his physical qualities and goalscoring ability, he possesses pace, athleticism, awareness, good link-up play, technical attributes and vision, as well as an ability to get into good attacking positions or create space for teammates with his intelligent runs off the ball.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/entry/romelu-lukaku-belgium-world-cup_n_5b43f48be4b0c523e261dc2d |title=The World Cup's Most Brilliant Player Can Dominate Without Scoring |website=HuffPost |last1=Waldron |first1=Travis |date=9 July 2018 |access-date=31 July 2019 |archive-date=31 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190731132256/https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/entry/romelu-lukaku-belgium-world-cup_n_5b43f48be4b0c523e261dc2d |url-status=live }}</ref> Although he was once criticised by pundits for his limited defensive contribution, he has since been praised by his managers for his work-rate off the ball.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/international-football/2017/11/27/5a1bf2dee5fdea8c6c8b463d.html |title=No goal, no problem as Mourinho hails Lukaku's work rate |newspaper=Marca |location=Spain |date=27 November 2017 |access-date=31 July 2019 |archive-date=31 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190731132707/https://www.marca.com/en/football/international-football/2017/11/27/5a1bf2dee5fdea8c6c8b463d.html |url-status=live }}</ref> However, despite his ability, he has also come into criticism in the media at times over his movement and first touch.<ref name="paradox">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/feb/28/romelu-lukaku-manchester-united-criticism-premier-league |title=The Lukaku paradox: goals, moments of brilliance … and clumsiness |newspaper=The Guardian |last1=Wilson |first1=Jonathan |date=28 February 2019 |access-date=31 July 2019 |archive-date=29 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729230748/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/feb/28/romelu-lukaku-manchester-united-criticism-premier-league |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/manchester-united-arsenal-romelu-lukaku-pogba-rashford-solskjaer-goals-2019-news-a8816926.html |title=Arsenal vs Manchester United: Romelu Lukaku defies recent form to frustrate on big stage once again |newspaper=The Independent |last1=Delaney |first1=Miguel |date=11 March 2019 |access-date=31 July 2019 |archive-date=31 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190731132252/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/manchester-united-arsenal-romelu-lukaku-pogba-rashford-solskjaer-goals-2019-news-a8816926.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/jul/21/romelu-lukaku-manchester-united-success-kevin-de-bruyne |title=Romelu Lukaku no Messi but he'll thrive at Old Trafford, says Kevin De Bruyne |newspaper=The Guardian |last1=Jackson |first1=Jamie |date=21 July 2017 |access-date=31 July 2019 |archive-date=31 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190731132251/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/jul/21/romelu-lukaku-manchester-united-success-kevin-de-bruyne |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thescore.com/chlg/news/1332028 |title=Winners and losers of Lukaku's pricey move to Manchester United |website=The Score |last1=Rouse |first1=Daniel |date=10 July 2017 |access-date=27 August 2019 |archive-date=30 October 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231030223551/https://www.thescore.com/chlg/news/1332028 |url-status=live }}</ref>

===Influences===
In a 2016 interview with [[ESPN]], Lukaku named [[Didier Drogba]] and [[Nicolas Anelka]] as the two strikers who made him want to play for Chelsea, but said that [[Ronaldo (Brazilian footballer)|Ronaldo]] was his idol: "Ronaldo changed football. He was the one you would look at. You would see him doing [[Step over|step-overs]] and you were thinking: 'Who does this?' You would see defenders falling over and you were like: 'Wow'. The goals that he scored, and at crucial times. He scored goals where you were like: 'Oh man, this is not serious.'"<ref name="idol"/> Crediting the former Brazilian striker as his major influence as a kid, Lukaku added: "He changed the dimension of a striker. He was fast, he can [[Dribbling#Association football|dribble]] like a winger, run like a sprinter, he was as strong as an ox."<ref name="idol"/> When mentioned that he shares certain characteristics with the Brazilian, Lukaku responded: "Be like Ronaldo? There is only one Ronaldo."<ref name="idol">{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Rory |title=Ronaldo deserves more credit as one of the game's greatest players |url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/club/brazil/205/blog/post/2840087/ronaldo-deserves-more-credit-as-one-of-the-games-best |publisher=ESPN |access-date=25 August 2018 |date=30 March 2016 |archive-date=25 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825143342/http://www.espn.com/soccer/club/brazil/205/blog/post/2840087/ronaldo-deserves-more-credit-as-one-of-the-games-best |url-status=live }}</ref>

==Personal life==
Lukaku was born in [[Antwerp]], Belgium<ref name="ESPN">{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/player/_/id/139437/romelu-lukaku?cc=5739|title=Romelu Lukaku|website=ESPN Soccernet|access-date=28 March 2011|archive-date=21 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110121221053/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/player/_/id/139437/romelu-lukaku?cc=5739|url-status=dead}}</ref> to [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|Congolese]] parents.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44521723 |title=World Cup 2018: Romelu Lukaku says some Belgians 'want to see me fail' |website=BBC Sport |date=18 June 2018 |accessdate=25 September 2018 |archive-date=28 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181128030334/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44521723 |url-status=live }}</ref> His father, [[Roger Lukaku]],<ref name="TDD">{{cite news|last=Wilson|first=Jeremy|title=Jose Mourinho and Real Madrid rival Chelsea for 'new Didier Drogba'|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/chelsea/8091041/Jose-Mourinho-and-Real-Madrid-rival-Chelsea-for-new-Didier-Drogba.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/chelsea/8091041/Jose-Mourinho-and-Real-Madrid-rival-Chelsea-for-new-Didier-Drogba.html |archive-date=10 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|access-date=6 August 2011|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=28 October 2010|location=London}}{{cbignore}}</ref> played professional football and was [[Cap (association football)|capped]] at international level by [[DR Congo national football team|Zaire]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Menama Lukaku |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/statisticsandrecords/players/player=93204/ |publisher=FIFA |access-date=6 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109153304/http://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/statisticsandrecords/players/player%3D93204/ |archive-date=9 November 2012 }}</ref> He has a younger brother named [[Jordan Lukaku|Jordan]], who has progressed through the youth academy at Anderlecht.<ref name="TDD" /> His cousin [[Boli Bolingoli-Mbombo]] plays as a left-sided winger or defender for [[Standard Liège]].

Lukaku was the subject of a television documentary series called [[:nl:De School Van Lukaku|''De School Van Lukaku'']] (Lukaku's School) shown on the Dutch-language [[Eén]] network. The reality show followed the teenage Lukaku and his classmates during the course of a year at the Saint-Guidon Institute, a school in [[Brussels]], where the footballer was based while with the Anderlecht youth team.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://socqer.com/questions/819/is-it-true-that-chelsea-striker-romelu-lukaku-starred-in-a-documentary-tv-series-about-his-schooldays/#answer_922 |title=Is it true Romelu Lukaku starred in a documentary tv series about his schooldays? |website=Socqer.com |access-date=7 August 2011 |archive-date=2 November 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111102225242/http://socqer.com/questions/819/is-it-true-that-chelsea-striker-romelu-lukaku-starred-in-a-documentary-tv-series-about-his-schooldays/#answer_922 |url-status=usurped }}</ref> In 2009, the series followed the school as it made a field trip to [[London]], visiting Stamford Bridge. Lukaku said at the time: "What a stadium. If one day in my life I will cry, it will be the day I play here. I love Chelsea."<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/chelsea/8687246/Chelseas-new-signing-Romelu-Lukaku-says-move-to-Stamford-Bridge-is-a-dream-come-true.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/chelsea/8687246/Chelseas-new-signing-Romelu-Lukaku-says-move-to-Stamford-Bridge-is-a-dream-come-true.html |archive-date=10 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |title=Chelsea new signing Romelu Lukaku says move to Stamford Bridge is a dream come true |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=8 August 2011 }}{{cbignore}}</ref> In addition to his native French and Dutch, Lukaku can speak fluent English, Portuguese, Italian, Spanish and a Congolese Swahili dialect, and can also understand German.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/west-brom-feature-chris-lepkowski-191038|title=West Brom feature: Chris Lepkowski talks to multi-lingual Romelu Lukaku about his life and career|last=Lepkowski|first=Chris|newspaper=Birmingham Mail|date=24 August 2012|access-date=24 August 2016|archive-date=18 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918073151/http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/west-brom-feature-chris-lepkowski-191038|url-status=live}}</ref> Lukaku has stated his biggest idol was Didier Drogba.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/everton/12040212/Romelu-Lukaku-He-is-my-idol-but-I-am-not-the-new-Didier-Drogba-I-am-my-own-player.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220110/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/everton/12040212/Romelu-Lukaku-He-is-my-idol-but-I-am-not-the-new-Didier-Drogba-I-am-my-own-player.html |archive-date=10 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|title=Romelu Lukaku: He is my idol, but I am not the new Didier Drogba – I am my own player|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=8 December 2015 }}{{cbignore}}</ref>

Lukaku is a practising [[Catholic Church|Catholic]], praying frequently before and after matches. He made the pilgrimage to [[Lourdes]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |first=May |last=Bulman |title=Romelu Lukaku: British tabloids wrongly claim black Christian footballer is 'devout Muslim' |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/romelu-lukaku-british-tabloids-christian-black-devout-muslim-manchester-united-daily-mail-sun-a7862506.html |newspaper=The Independent |date=27 July 2017 |access-date=31 July 2017 |archive-date=18 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618213257/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/romelu-lukaku-british-tabloids-christian-black-devout-muslim-manchester-united-daily-mail-sun-a7862506.html |url-status=live }}</ref> He is a [[Teetotalism|teetotaller]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/news/2018/oct/18/miqdaad-versi-very-polite-fight-against-british-media-islamophobia|title=One man's (very polite) fight against media Islamophobia|date=18 October 2018|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=2 August 2020|archive-date=31 July 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200731141407/https://www.theguardian.com/news/2018/oct/18/miqdaad-versi-very-polite-fight-against-british-media-islamophobia|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Media and endorsements===
Lukaku was the first Premier League player to join [[Jay-Z]]'s management agency [[Roc Nation Sports]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rocnation.com/romelu-lukaku/|title=ROMELU LUKAKU|website=roc nation|date=1 March 2018|access-date=1 March 2018|archive-date=23 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180423023758/http://rocnation.com/romelu-lukaku/|url-status=live}}</ref> In June 2018, he signed a record sponsorship deal with German sportswear company [[Puma SE|Puma]], the company's largest endorsement deal ever.<ref>{{cite news |title=Manchester United's Romelu Lukaku signs record Puma sponsorship deal |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/manchester-united/story/3526838/manchester-uniteds-romelu-lukaku-signs-record-puma-sponsorship-deal |publisher=ESPN |date=19 June 2018 |access-date=19 June 2018 |archive-date=19 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619140822/http://www.espn.co.uk/football/manchester-united/story/3526838/manchester-uniteds-romelu-lukaku-signs-record-puma-sponsorship-deal |url-status=live }}</ref> Lukaku is also known by his nickname, "Lakaka", given to him by fans. This nickname is often used sardonically to mock Lukaku's poor performances and gained popularity after his appearances in the [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022 World Cup]] and the [[2023 UEFA Champions League final|2023 Champions League final]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Lakaka |url=https://knowyourmeme.com/memes/lakaka |website=Know Your Meme |date=2 December 2022 |publisher=Literally Media Ltd |access-date=1 July 2024}}</ref>

===Activism===
[[File:Kneeling for Black Lives Matter - Football.jpg|thumb|200px|Lukaku, at the centre, with the [[Belgium national football team|Belgian national team]] in 2021]]

Lukaku has spoken out against [[racism]] he suffered while playing football, particularly the 2019–20 Serie A season, his first year playing in Italy.<ref>{{cite news|title=A Soccer Star's View of Racist Abuse|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/22/sports/soccer/romelu-lukaku-inter-italy-racism.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=22 December 2019 |access-date=10 September 2021|archive-date=9 September 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210909160530/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/22/sports/soccer/romelu-lukaku-inter-italy-racism.html|url-status=live |last1=Smith |first1=Rory }}</ref>

In 2020, Lukaku honoured [[George Floyd]] by kneeling and keeping one fist high in support of [[Black Lives Matter]] when he scored in a game with Inter against Sampdoria.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Lukaku scores as Inter return with win|language=en-GB|work=BBC Sport|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51563514|access-date=10 September 2021|archive-date=10 September 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210910063725/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51563514|url-status=live}}</ref> This symbolic action was inspired by American football player [[Colin Kaepernick]] who kneeled during the [[The Star-Spangled Banner|national anthem]] before every game in 2016 as a peaceful manner of protest against police brutality towards people of colour. Since then, Lukaku and other players in Europe has taken an active role to [[taking the knee|take a knee]].

